<HEADLINE> Improvements in Cargo Services at HK New Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Air Cargo Terminals
Ltd. (HACTL), the operator of SuperTerminal 1 at Hong Kong's
one-month-old new international airport, Thursday announced
improvements in its provision of outbound cargo handling services.
</P>
<P>
The improvements will lead up to the handling of all export
cargo from August 16, an official of the HACTL said.
</P>
<P>
With effect from 23:59 on August 9, HACTL will handle on all
outbound passenger flights, two pallets, plus 500 kilograms of
loose cargo.
</P>
<P>
This cargo can be delivered by shippers and agents into the
SuperTerminal 1 facility with effect from 23:59 on August 8.
</P>
<P>
By 23:59 on August 15, all restrictions on export handling at
SuperTerminal 1 will be lifted and at this time HACTL will be able
to process all its customers' requirements at either SuperTerminal
1 or Terminal 2 at Kai Tak.
</P>
<P>
HACTL also announced that, as of 23:59 on August 11, cargo on
all Cathay Pacific inbound flights, both passenger and freighter,
will be handled at SuperTerminal 1. This will greatly facilitate
the handling of transshipment cargo.
</P>
<P>
Anthony Charter, managing director of HACTL, said the recovery
plan of the SuperTerminal 1 is going according to schedule, with
the aim being to handle all outbound and inbound cargo through
SuperTerminal 1 by the end of August.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the overall progress to date in the recovery
plan, Charter said that since the recovery plan was implemented at
23:59 on July 18, tonnage handled has been steadily increasing.
"Last week for example, the tonnage handled by HACTL was at 80
percent of normal levels," he said.
</P>
<P>
Operation of the SuperTerminal 1 broke down after the new
airport at Chek Lap Kok went into commercial service on July 6 due
to computer problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
