<HEADLINE> UK Warns Iraq over Arms Inspections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook Thursday warned Iraq over suspending cooperation with U.N.
weapon inspectors, saying it would only prolong economic
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's statement threatening to end cooperation is "a
transparent attempt to raise the stakes before Richard Butler
reports to the United Nations." Robin Cook said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement was issued hours before Richard Butler, chief of
the U.N. Special Commission for disarmament in Iraq (UNSCOM), is
to brief U.N. members later Thursday on the current situation in
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Robin Cook said that Baghdad promised U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan in February that Iraq would cooperate fully and
unconditionally with UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the only way that Iraq can secure the
lifting of sanctions is to honor that undertaking rather than
seeking to impose new conditions.
</P>
<P>
"This latest move will only delay the moment when the Security
Council can consider the removal of sanctions." Cook said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
