<HEADLINE> Israeli, Palestinian Contacts Continue: Netanyahu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 6 (Xinhua) -- One day after the killing of
two Jewish settlers in the West Bank, Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu said contacts with the Palestinians on the
redeployment issue are continuing.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu told reporters in his office Thursday that he thought
an agreement could be reached with the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) over the second redeployment of Israeli troops in
the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
But he noted that the killing of Jewish settlers underscored
the need to make sure the Palestinians fulfilled their commitment
to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu also disclosed that he had a phone conversation with
PNA President Yasser Arafat two days before.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said he urged Arafat to act on the issue of
Palestinian commitment, especially security commitment, in order
to complete the current negotiations on the second
redeployment. No more detail is available.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Palestinian negotiators resumed direct talks last month
in a bid to unblock the peace process, which has been stalled for
months over the scope of the long-overdue redeployment. But no
progress has been made in Israel's acceptance of a U.S. initiative
for a 13.1 percent more withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Since two Jewish settlers were killed early Wednesday near the
West Bank city of Nablus, some right-wing members in the Israeli
government have called to halt talks with the Palestinians.
</P>
</TEXT>
