<HEADLINE> Richardson Urges Strong Response From Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council of
the United Nations would have to respond in a very strong and
unmistakable way amid Iraq's announcement that it had decided to
froze the cooperation with U.N. Weapons inspectors, U.S.
Ambassador to the United Nations said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters before the Security Council is to be
briefed by Richard Butler, Executive Chairman of the United
Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM), on his recent visit to Iraq,
Bill Richardson said Iraq had violated U.N. resolutions and the
Memorandum of Understanding reached between the country and the
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan Last February.
</P>
<P>
Richardson said Iraq would have to reverse itself on its
decision to refuse further cooperation with UNSCOM in charge of
dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction and the
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA).
</P>
<P>
Iraq announced on Wednesday that it was suspending cooperation
with UNSCOM led by Butler until it was restructured.
</P>
<P>
Butler visited Iraq on Monday. The first two rounds of
disarmament talks between Iraq's Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz
and the chief inspector broke down due to sharp differences.
Butler cut short his visit and returned to the headquarters of the
United Nations in New York on Wednesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
