<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Says Iraqi Action not in Conformity with MOU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said Thursday that Iraq's decision to suspend U.N. arms
inspection is not in conformity with U.N. resolutions and his
agreement reached with Iraq in February.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks in a brief question and answer session when
he arrived at the U.N. Headquarters here this morning.
</P>
<P>
To the question whether he saw Iraq's action violating the
February 23 memorandum of understanding which defused the crisis
in the arms inspection, Annan said:"We have been seeking full
compliance with all Security Council resolutions including the
MOU, and what has happened is not in conformity with that."
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General came here to hear a Security Council
briefing by Richard Butler, Executive Chairman of UNSCOM, or the
U.N. Special Commission for disarmament in Iraq, on his trip to
Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Butler came back to New York on Wednesday from Baghdad after
his talks with the Iraqi Government on the next disarmament steps
collapsed early this week.
</P>
<P>
Iraq announced Wednesday to suspend cooperation with U.N.
weapons inspectors until conditions it sets are met.
</P>
<P>
It demands equal representation of the member states of the
Security Council on the Special Commission, and a relocation of
UNSCOM headquarters to Geneva from New York to keep the Commission
away from direct U.S. influence.
</P>
<P>
Iraq also demands a rotation of UNSCOM chairmanship among the
five permanent members of the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's move was seen to be motivated by its aim to early lift
eight-year U.N. sanctions on it.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions were imposed in 1990 since the Iraqi invasion of
Kuwait, which triggered the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions will not be lifted until UNSCOM certifies that
Baghdad has destroyed all banned weapons.
</P>
<P>
Iraq said it has complied with the relevant U.N. resolutions,
but Butler's commission said it has not.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
