<HEADLINE> Triple Olympic Gold Medallist Smith Banned for Four Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Irish swimmer Michelle Smith,
winner of three gold medals at the 1996 Atlanta Olympics, was
banned from competition for four years on Thursday after being
found guilty of tampering with a drug test, the sport's world gove
rning body FINA said in Lausanne.
</P>
<P>
Smith, now called Michelle De Bruin, was banned by FINA after a
hearing last month had initially failed to reach a decision on her
future. The suspension will come into immediate effect, FINA said.
</P>
<P>
Smith's lawyer, Peter Lennon, said he would not comment on the
ruling until a news conference in Dublin on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The case against Smith, alleged that she used alcohol, a
masking agent, to tamper with a urine specimen she gave on January
10 at Kilkenny County, Republic of Ireland.
</P>
<P>
A potentially-lethal dose of whiskey found in a first urine
specimen was also detected in the back-up sample.
</P>
<P>
The 28-year-old had denied tampering with her test and said any
manipulation must have taken place without her knowledge.
</P>
<P>
The urine specimen was divided into A and B samples and sealed
in separate containers after it was given.
</P>
<P>
De Bruin won gold medals at the Atlanta Olympics in the 400m
freestyle, and 200 and 400m individual medley.
</P>
<P>
FINA ruled that all competition results in the six months
before a positive test must be annulled.
</P>
<P>
This means that Smith is likely to be stripped of the two gold
and two silver medals that she won at the European championships
in Seville, Spain, last summer.  
</P>
</TEXT>
