<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian FM to Meet Sudan's Rebel Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa will meet Sudan's rebel leader John Garang here next week
to discuss the ongoing efforts to end Sudan's 15-year-old civil
war, the Middle East News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Moussa and Garang, who commands the Sudanese Peoples'
Liberation Army (SPLA), will discuss the outcome of the peace
negotiations in May between Sudan's government and the opposition.
</P>
<P>
During the talks in Kenya, the two sides agreed to an
internationally supervised vote on self-determination for the
south, where the SPLA and government troops have been fighting for
control.
</P>
<P>
The predominantly Christian and animist south has been battling
for autonomy since 1983. Fightings, drought and famine have
conspired to claim more than 1.5 million lives.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the two sides declared a ceasefire to expedite
delivery of relief supplies to the famine-stricken Bahr al-Ghazal
province. The government has announced to expand ceasefire areas,
a decision welcomed by Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Foreign Ministry in a statement voiced hope that
such a move would herald good intentions to bring together all the
Sudanese to establish an overall peace and maintain the country's
integrity, sovereignty, stability and the welfare of its people.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt will never stop doing its best in order to reach these
objectives," the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
However, all the objective proved hard to come by. The peace
talks between Sudan's government and rebels started two days ago
under the auspices of the Intergovernmental Authority for
Development in the Ethiopian capital Addis Ababa reportedly ended
Thursday without progress.
</P>
<P>
The two sides failed to reach agreement on any of the topics.
Differences on self-determination in southern Sudan and border
demarcation there are still hindering the talks.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also argue over the relationship between religion
and the state. The southerners advocate a secular state while the
government says the overwhelming majority of the Sudanese people
want to apply the Islamic Sharia (law) in all Sudan except the
largely Christian south.
</P>
<P>
Sudan and Egypt are at odds over a border area and have traded
accusations of harboring each other's militants and oppositions,
but there are signs of a tentative thaw in relations in recent
months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
