<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sartaj Appointed Pakistan's New Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Finance Minister
Sartaj Aziz Thursday was appointed new foreign minister in place
of Gohar Ayub Khan who tendered his resignation in April.
</P>
<P>
An official notification to this effect was issued to Sartaj,
69, who had served as finance minister twice in the past seven
years, late Thursday evening, government officials said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Gohar was given the portfolio of minister of Water
and Power, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Sartaj told the private News Network International
(NNI) that Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif had formally asked him to
look after the Foreign Ministry and he was waiting for the
official notification.
</P>
<P>
He dispelled the impression given by the press that he was
being removed from the finance minister due to his failure to
manage the country's financial matters.
</P>
<P>
Sartaj said the prime minister took the decision in April this
year when Gohar decided to relinquish his charge as the foreign
minister.
</P>
<P>
Gohar, who requested the prime minister to change his present
post, said the Foreign Ministry keeps him away from his
electorates.
</P>
<P>
Sartaj, had served as finance minister from August 1990 to July
1993 during the first government led by Prime Minister Sharif and
was given the same portfolio in Sharif's new cabinet, which was
sworn in in February 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
