<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands Hold Anti-nuclear Demonstration in New Delhi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Even as Indian and Pakistani
troops exchange fire in Kashmir, thousands of Indians including
workers, intellectuals, retired military personnel, journalists,
students and scientists staged an anti-nuclear demonstration here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said almost simultaneously thousands of
Indians shouted anti-nuclear slogans in Mumbai, Calcutta,
Bangalore, Trivandrum and other cities.
</P>
<P>
In the old city of Delhi, the demonstrators held placards and
shouted slogans as "(we) want bread, no bomb" and "(we) want jobs,
no nuclear weapons".
</P>
<P>
The demonstration was organized by the Citizen Against Nuclear
Weapons, a civilian organization in India, which said it provided
the function for citizens to voice their anger and opposition
against the recent nuclear tests both in India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, three top former Pakistani and Indian military
officers urged the leaders of the two neighbors Wednesday to
eliminate nuclear weapons from their arsenal and resolve their
disputes through peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
Former Indian Naval Chief Admiral L. Ramdas (retired), former
Vice-Chief of the Pakistan Air Force Air Marshal Zafar A.
Choudhury and former Indian Army Lieutenant General Gurbir
Mansingh said in New Delhi that recent development in the field of
nuclear weapons and the means of their delivery are a serious
threat to the well-being of South Asia.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement signed by the three officers, they urged
governments of the two countries to confine nuclear research and
development strictly to peaceful and beneficent spheres. 
</P>
</TEXT>
