<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vucic: Yugoslavia Favors Diplomatic Solution to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Yugoslav Press Minister
Alexander Vucic Thursday stressed here that Belgrade supported a
diplomatic solution to the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Vucic said that his country was
making every possible effort towards a peaceful solution to Kosovo
where ethnic Albanians make up 90 percent of its nearly 2 million
population and have been demanding independence. Any other way for
a solution but the political one would be foolish, he added.
</P>
<P>
The minister reiterated that Yugoslavia opposed intervention in
Kosovo by the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) because it
would violate international rules and constitute intervention in
the domestic affairs of a country.
</P>
<P>
Vucic also denied a press report of a mass grave containing 567
bodies near the Kosovo town of Orahovac, saying that German
reporter Erik Ratfelder had not even visited the area in question.
</P>
<P>
He said that Yugoslavia respected the rights of ethnic
minorities and no one could accuse the country of human rights
violations.
</P>
<P>
The press reports of an Orahovac massacre triggered immediate
reaction from European countries. Austria, which holds the current
EU presidency, asked the EU observer mission in Kosovo to verify
the reports urgently.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
