<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Ally in South Lebanon Concerned About </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 6 (Xinhua) -- You may leave South Lebanon, but
what about us ? -- Israeli-allied South Lebanon Army (SLA)
Thursday posed the question to Israel which is seeking a
withdrawal agreement with Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Orient radio quoted the SLA commander Antoine Lahd as
saying that the arrangement for south Lebanon, including the
residents and SLA members, should be a part of any agreement or
deal which would be reached between Beirut government and Israel.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark at a ceremony at Arslan in the Israeli
occupied zone to mark the end of a camp organized by Israeli
authority for Lebanese children living in the south.
</P>
<P>
He said the common interest for Israelis and Lebanese in south
Lebanon is the security and the peace.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that Lebanon and Israel reach an
agreement concerning the Israeli pullout from the south.
</P>
<P>
Israel has been occupying a 1,200-square-kilometer border strip
in south Lebanon and called it "security zone" in 1985 to protect
its north from Lebanese guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Some 2,000 SLA militiamen are helping Israeli occupying forces
patrol the enclave and controlling Lebanon's Christian-dominated
town of Jezzine which faces the occupied zone.
</P>
<P>
But the Israeli and SLA troops have met a tough resistance from
guerrillas. The heavy losses the Israeli forces suffered in south
Lebanon have forced the Jewish state into offering a withdrawal
proposal on the condition of the Beirut government security
guarantee for its northern borders.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon rejected the offer made in April and asked Israel to
unconditionally leave the occupied land.
</P>
<P>
But the proposal provoked the fear of SLA militiamen for their
uncertain future and some of them even have publicly applied for
Israeli visa.
</P>
<P>
SLA is considered by the Lebanese government as the nation's
traitor and its leader Lahd has been sentenced to death in
absentia by the Lebanese military court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
