<HEADLINE> SCCC Urges Indonesia to Punish Anti-Chinese Attackers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Chinese Chamber of
Commerce (SCCC) issued a statement Friday calling on the
Indonesian government to punish anti-Chinese attackers and take
concrete measures to guarantee the life, safety and dignity of the
ethnic-Chinese in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The statement also expressed welcome to a reported affirmation
by an Indonesian presidential envoy that his government has been
working on legislation to ensure the equal civil rights for
ethnic-Chinese and has set up a joint fact-finding committee to
investigate incidents including cases of molesting and raping
ethnic-Chinese women.
</P>
<P>
Quoting Thursday's reports from a Malaysian newspaper, the
statement said Indonesian presidential envoy Iman Taufik, while
speaking at a press conference in Kuala Lumpur, conceded that the
ethnic Chinese were suffering from injustice in his country in the
past 30 years and he affirmed that his government has drafted a
law bill to stipulate the human rights and responsibilities of the
citizens including the ethnic-Chinese.
</P>
<P>
The statement said SCCC welcomes the legislative move taken by
the Indonesian government and the formation of the fact-finding
committee to investigate the crimes committed against ethnic
Chinese, particularly the atrocities against ethnic-Chinese women
during the riot in May.
</P>
<P>
"We are very much concerned about the current plight of the
ethnic-Chinese in Indonesia and hope the Indonesian authority to
complete investigations as soon as possible, publish the results
to the international community and severely punish those
committing monstrous and unforgivable crimes against
ethnic-Chinese Indonesians," the SCCC statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement urged the Indonesian government to do more to
guarantee the life, safety and dignity of the ethnic Chinese.
</P>
</TEXT>
