<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bhutanese Refugees Appeal for UN Help </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Some Bhutanese refugees here
Friday appealed to the United Nations High Commissioner for
Refugees (UNHCR) to help resolve their problem.
</P>
<P>
As initiated by the Appeal Movement Coordination Council, an
organization of Bhutanese refugees based in Nepal, 6,000
applications from 6,000 families were presented Friday to the
UNHCR office in Kathmandu.
</P>
<P>
The refugees said in the applications that "we're genuine
Bhutanese refugees, so UNHCR should verify us. We should not be
stateless, so save us from being without any state."
</P>
<P>
Ratan Gajamer, secretary-general of the Appeal Movement
Coordination Council, said that more refugee families living in
various camps in eastern Nepal are also sending in their
applications.
</P>
<P>
About 100,000 Bhutanese refugees are staying in eight U.N.-run
camps in eastern Nepal after being forced to flee Bhutan in 1989
and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Nepal and Bhutan have held seven rounds of ministerial talks on
the issue but without any result. Bhutan said that it would take
back only those genuine Bhutanese refugees.
</P>
<P>
India, which handles Bhutan's foreign and defense affairs, has
refused to get involved in the matter, saying it is a bilateral
issue.
</P>
<P>
But Nepali Prime Minister Girija Prasad Koirala said that the
attitudes of Bhutan and India were positive when he held talks
with leaders of the two countries about the issue on the sidelines
of the 10th summit of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation held in late July.
</P>
<P>
He said that ministerial talks between Nepal and Bhutan would
resume soon on the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
