<HEADLINE> Six Dead, 57 Injured in Dar es Salaam Explosion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The death toll of the
explosion at the United States Embassy in the Tanzanian capital on
Friday morning has risen to six, while 57 others have been
injured, 15 of them critically, hospital sources said.
</P>
<P>
So far, three of the dead -- two women and one man -- have been
confirmed as Tanzanian citizens, Jezza Waziri with the Muhimbili
Medical Center (MMC) told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
However, it is not immediately known whether the three dead
Tanzanians work for the embassy or they went there to seek visas
or for other purposes when the bomb exploded.
</P>
<P>
David Mwakyusa, a spokesman for the Muhimbili Medical Center,
where the patients were admitted, said all of the injured being
treated are Tanzanians.
</P>
<P>
Medical sources said one injured U.S. citizen at the embassy
refused to go to hospital.
</P>
<P>
The MMC is packed with policemen and relatives of the victims,
and ambulances could be seen rushing in and out.
</P>
<P>
Six hours after the explosion, the Tanzanian government had
still not issued any statement on it. Simeon Ileta, the spokesman
for the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and International Cooperation,
declined to comment on the incident.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to tell you when we are ready," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
