<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Gorges Dam Tested by Biggest Flood This Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Three Gorges Dam, currently
under construction in the middle reaches of the Yangtze River,
has withstood the heaviest flooding this season, with this early
evening water flow rates reaching as high 58,000 cu.m. per second.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the dam and other facilities involved in
China's largest-ever water conservancy project has continued
unimpeded, and travelers stranded upstream from the dam site since
traffic was forced to be closed Tuesday have been evacuated.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges Dam has been under the constant threat of
heavy flooding since the beginning of July, with three flood
crests reaching maximum flow rates of 57,700 cu.m. per second
passing through the section by July 25.
</P>
<P>
The fourth flood crest formed on August 2, and torrential rains
have created surging discharges from the section.
</P>
<P>
According to hydrological data stored at Yichang Hydrological
Station, the dam site has not met a discharge of 72,300 cubic
meters per second over the past 110 years, whose chance of
occurrence is once every two decades.
</P>
<P>
Flood control facilities at the Three Gorges Project have been
constructed in line with standards for withstanding 20-year
floods, while the second stage cofferdam is built to withstand
100-year floods with discharge rates of 83,700 cu.m. per second.
</P>
<P>
Some 230,000 stranded travelers had been evacuated from areas
upstream from the dam by 06:00 this evening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Flood-hit Jiujiang City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Following is a backgrounder of
Jiujiang City whose defense embankments partially collapsed at
12:30 p.m. today, and water two meters deep began to inundate
the western part of the city.
</P>
<P>
Jiujiang City, along the southern bank of the middle reaches of
the Yangtze River, lies in the northern parts of east China's
Jiangxi Province, and the city proper covers an area of 42 square
kilometers, with a population of 500,000.
</P>
<P>
The city borders on Anhui, Hubei, and Hunan provinces, 135
kilometers north of Nanchang, the provincial capital. It is also
Jiangxi's major bases of petrochemical and textile industries. Its
annual exports of overcoats account for half of the country's
total.
</P>
<P>
China's major south-north artery, the Beijing-Kowloon Railway
runs through it. The Jiujiang Port is the province's only waterway
leading to the sea. In addition, the city opened air routes to
Japan, Hong Kong, and Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
It has a lot of lakes and rivers, and the most well-known is
the Poyang Lake, the country's largest freshwater lake. For weeks,
the 3,976-square-kilometer lake has maintained record flooding
water levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
