<HEADLINE> France Fears Destabilization of Great Lakes Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- France has expressed its fear that
the continued fighting between government forces and rebels in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (D.R. Congo) will further destabilize
the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
D.R. Congo President Laurent-Desire Kabila said on Thursday
that he would send the war back to where it came from, accusing
Rwanda of being the origin of the rebellion.
</P>
<P>
"The risks of destabilization of the region are troubling,"
said French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Anne Gazeau-Secret.
</P>
<P>
Fighting continues in several parts of the D.R. Congo. The
Banyamulenge rebels control a key triangle area in the southwest
not far from Kinshasa, the French Foreign Ministry said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The spokeswoman said that the fighting in the Kivu region of
eastern Congo and other places "goes against what is wished".
</P>
<P>
She also called for respect of the territorial integrity of
D.R.Congo by all its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
"We appeal for, as the Secretary-General of the United Nations
did, respect of territorial integrity of D.R.Congo and respect of
civilians, in the hope that this crisis can be resolved by an end
of hostilities," she said.
</P>
<P>
She said France would watch closely the summit on Saturday in
Zimbabwe by the heads of state of seven nations in the region,
including President Kabila and his Rwandan counterpart, Pasterur
Bizimungu, which aimed to seek a way out of the crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
