<HEADLINE> Clinton Watches Developments Concerning Blasts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton,
awakened at 5:30 a.m. with the news of the bomb blasts near the
U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania, is watching developments
closely, a State Department official said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"He was watching it very closely," the official said. "We're
just trying to get more information. Right now information about
the two bombings is very sketchy."
</P>
<P>
Clinton was informed of the attacks by National Security
Adviser Sandy Berger.
</P>
<P>
The bombs went exploded at or near the embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania between 10:40 and 10:45 a.m. local time on Friday, and
caused massive damage, with deaths and injuries in both blasts,
State Department spokesman Lee McClenny said.
</P>
<P>
"There are numerous people dead," he said. "The rear of the
embassy in Nairobi (the capital of Kenya) is reported to have
collapsed."
</P>
<P>
U.S. embassies around the world had been put on heightened
security alert, McClenny said.
</P>
<P>
"There was no warning and there has been no claim of
responsibility," he said. "They were terrorist attacks."
</P>
<P>
The State Department has set up a task force on the bombings
and the U.S. government is sending personnel and equipment to the
sites.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who has been notified
the bombings, is returning to Washington from a private visit to
Italy, where she was scheduled to attend the weekend wedding of
her spokesman James Rubin.
</P>
<P>
The United States has a C-141 medical supply plane based in
Germany with medical supplies that is ready to go whenever
necessary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
