<HEADLINE> Tung Calls on HK Residents to Help Flood Stricken People in Mainland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) here Friday
called on Hong Kong residents to donate to the victims of the
serious flood along the Yangtze River in China's mainland.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to a media session Friday afternoon, Tung said that
this year's flood in the mainland is the most serious one in the
past 50 years, with 28 provinces and cities and 240 million people
along the Yangtze River being affected by the flood.
</P>
<P>
Tung expressed his admiration for the millions of soldiers and
civilians along the Yangtze River who are fighting against the
flood.
</P>
<P>
"At this difficult moment, the people in the flooding areas
badly need our support," Tung said. People in the SAR and the
mainland are all Chinese people and should care about each other
and help each other at the difficult moment, he added.
</P>
<P>
Tung said that many voluntary bodies in Hong Kong have started
their donation activities and he called on Hong Kong residents to
support these activities.
</P>
<P>
He said that the SAR government has allocated nine million HK
dollars (1.15 million U.S. dollars) as relief fund to help the
people in the flooding areas.
</P>
<P>
Tung said that he understood Hong Kong residents' difficulties
at present due to the bad economic situation. "How much money you
donate is not important," Tung said. "What is important is to show
your love," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
