<HEADLINE> Sweden's GDP Up 4.1 Percent in Second Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Sweden posted a 4.1 percent
increase in its gross domestic product (GDP) during second quarter
of the year, against the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Private consumption was up 2.6 percent and gross investments
rose nearly 10 percent, a new high in economic growth recorded
over the past three years, figures from Statistics Sweden showed.
</P>
<P>
The domestic consumption and the rising investments, rather
than the exports, were believed to be the main forces behind the
growth.
</P>
<P>
Denmark, Norway and Finland have enjoyed stronger economic growth
following the recession at the start of the 1990s while Sweden has
been seen as lagging behind. 
</P>
