Friday, the baht was once traded at 42.20 against the U.S.
dollar before gaining some ground to close at 41.87/41.97.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Thursday, the baht passed the 41 psychological level
for the first time in the recent month.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the devaluation of the baht in the past two
days was triggered by the speculative attack on the Hong Kong
dollar which began on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Thai Deputy Prime Minister and Commerce Minister Supachai
Panitchpakdi said Friday that the speculative attack on the Hong
Kong dollar was a problem of the whole region, which will have
adverse effect on Thailand's economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
The weak Japanese yen also added to pressure on the Thai baht.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Stock Exchange of Thailand (SET) index recorded
falls in all five trading days through this week. The SET index
lost 19.18 points or 7 percent from 266.72 points last Friday to
247.54 points.
</P>
<P>
On Friday only, the SET index lowered 4.53 points with a
trading value of only 890 million baht (21.7 million U.S.
dollars). 
