<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 7  IBM Ending Olympic Deal in Cost Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 7 (Xinhua) -- International Business Machines
Corp. is pulling out as a world-wide sponsor of the Olympic Games,
abruptly severing a 38-year marketing relationship with an
about-face that underscores the high cost of linking corporate
marketing to sports, the Wall Street Journal reported today.
</P>
<P>
The pulling came after several months of futile negotiations, IBM
said. The company is choosing to walk away rather than lock up an
eight-year deal with the International Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
One apparent sticking point is IBM wanted local organizing
committees to start bearing some of the technology costs, the paper
said. The world computer giant spent more than 100 million U.S.
dollars to sponsor the 1998 Winter Games and provided much of the
technology behind it free of charge.
</P>
<P>
IBM said that the two sides could not agree on how much money the
local Olympic organizers should pay IBM and how much IBM should have
to give away in exchange for marketing rights to the Olympic rings.
</P>
<P>
The bailout by IBM means that its sponsorship of the next
Olympics, the 2000 Summer Games in Sydney, Australia, may be the
company's last. IBM said that it is "fully committed to making the
millennium games an outstanding event" and "will market it heavily."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Corrupt Police Officials Under Arrest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Two public security bureau
officials in Handan, north China's Hebei Province, have been
arrested on charges of accepting bribes to protect the owner of
two businesses involving in gambling and prostitution.
</P>
<P>
Wei Guo'an, deputy chief of the Hanshan District Public
Security Bureau, and Sun Jiping, deputy chief of the Handan City
Public Security Bureau allegedly received 250,000 yuan and 40,000
yuan respectively from business owner Song Xinzhong for issuing
licenses to the game halls and shielding Song from police
investigations.
</P>
<P>
Protection provided by the officials enabled Song to amass
profits of well over one million yuan since 1996.
</P>
<P>
The local bureau has forced closure of the two businesses, and
more than ten local law enforcement officers, taxation, cultural
and public security department personnel involved in the case are
under investigation.
</P>
<P>
In another development, 46 people who used fake documents to
gain law enforcement jobs have been dismissed from service in
Wanning City, south China's Hainan Province.
</P>
<P>
Illegal activities by law enforcement officers have been the
focus of public outrage in recent years, and extensive efforts
have been made to eliminate corrupt elements since the new
minister of Public Security, president of the Supreme People's
Court and procurator-general of the Supreme People's Procuratorate
were elected by the National People's Congress, China's top
legislature, during its annual session in March this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
