<HEADLINE> China Drafts Plan to Solve Education Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese official said here
today that the Ministry of Education is formulating a plan for
improving education for the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The action plan is part of efforts to implement the country's
policy of "modernizing the nation through the development of
science, technology and education", according Education
Vice-Minister Wei Yu.
</P>
<P>
Wei said that major tasks for the education sector will include
promoting compulsory education, eradicating illiteracy and
developing education in poverty-stricken and minority areas.
</P>
<P>
More than 97 percent school-age children were enrolled in
primary schools during 1997, with a noticeable closure in the
disparity education opportunities for male and female children,
according to Wei.
</P>
<P>
"By the end of 1997, nine-year compulsory education had been
introduced to areas with 65 percent of the nation's population,
whereas six-year elementary compulsory education had been
available in areas with 90 percent of the total population," said
Wei.
</P>
<P>
Efforts to universalize the compulsory education program have
entered a critical period, said Wei during a meeting with
officials of the United Nations Children's Fund (Unicef) and
various Chinese ministries and organizations.
</P>
<P>
The goal of the meeting, sponsored by Unicef, was to review the
cooperative program between Unicef and departments of the Chinese
government, including the Ministry of Education.
</P>
<P>
Wei pointed to difficulties in the education sector in
poverty-stricken and minority areas and noted that the country is
challenged by new educational problems, including programs
involving children of the floating population and laid-off
workers, as well as environmental education and anti-drug
education.  
</P>
</TEXT>
