<HEADLINE> Soccer Poland Faces Ban from International Stage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Poland is facing a ban from
international stage after world soccer's governing body FIFA
refused on Friday to extend its midnight deadline for the
government and the national football federation (PZPN) to settle
their dispute.
</P>
<P>
FIFA and, by implication its European counterpart UEFA, will
ban Poland's international team and leading clubs from their
competitions unless the two sides resolve a crisis sparked by the
sacking of PZPN's top officials by the government in May.
</P>
<P>
FIFA said on Friday it had refused a request from Poland's
sports minister for the midnight deadline to be extended.
</P>
<P>
Polish sports ministry officials said the two sides appeared to
be making no progress in ending their dispute, although behind the
scenes talks were continuing.
</P>
<P>
LKS Lodz, Wisla Krakow, Polonia Warsaw and Polish Cup winners
Amica Wronki are due to play in UEFA competitions next week, with
Lodz facing Manchester United in an European Cup contest at Old
Trafford on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
If the ban goes ahead Poland would also be expelled from the
qualifying competition for the 2000 European championships
starting next month. 
</P>
