<HEADLINE> IGAD Meeting on Sudan Conflict Ends Without </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The third session of the
Inter-Governmental Authority on Development (IGAD) ministerial
sub-committee on south Sudan conflict ended here Friday without
result.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held here, Bonaya Adhi Godana, Minister
of Foreign Affairs of Kenya and chairman of the sub-committee,
read out a communique, saying "the government of Sudan and the
Sudan People's Liberation Movement (SPLM) were unable to agree on
the definition of south Sudan for the purpose of conducting a
referendum."
</P>
<P>
The parties have been unable to reach a common ground on the
question of state and religion, said the communique.
</P>
<P>
The sub-committee called upon both parties to continue
searching for an agreement on this issue.
</P>
<P>
On the interim arrangements, the sub-committee acknowledged
the submission of the government of Sudan and the SPLM on their
respective positions which is considered a step forward and
directed the special envoys to continue consultations with the
two sides with the view to bridging the existing gap.
</P>
<P>
The sub-committee agreed to continue with consultations until
an amicable solution is reached and to that end, further agreed
to convene the fourth round of negotiations within six months, in
Nairobi, Kenya, according to the communique.
</P>
<P>
After the press conference held by the IGAD sub-committee, the
delegations of the Sudanese government and the SPLM also held
press conference respectively, explaining their respective
positions on the program of the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The two previous Sudan peace talks were held in Nairobi in
October 1997 and May 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
