<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon's Internet Market Grows Rapidly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's internet market is
growing rapidly, with the number of users jumping from 5,000 in
1996 jumping to 40,000 this year, a senior ministry official said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Al-Minaim Yousuf, general-director of the Investment Department
of the Posts and Telecommunication Ministry, said in a radio
interview that Lebanese internet subscribers represent half of the
total in all Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
The revenues from the internet service have reached 1 million
U.S. dollars each month, the official added.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the rapid growth of the internet service to the
ministry's effective policy to fully open the market to the
private sector.
</P>
<P>
So far, there are a total of five commercial companies in
Lebanon providing internet service.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the ministry has hammered out a huge
project to promote this modern technology across the country.
</P>
<P>
The state-run Lebanese University has hooked up to the internet
and other governmental institutions and departments are moving in
this direction, Yousuf said.
</P>
<P>
The internet node was first introduced to Lebanon in 1993 by
the privately-owned American University of Beirut and on a
commercial basis in September 1995 by Data Mangement company.
</P>
<P>
The early subscribers consisted mainly of students and
professors, most of whom were Lebanese from abroad already
familiar with the on-line services.
</P>
<P>
But most of the subscribers currently belong to the corporate
field, especially in economy, finance and industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0072 </DOCNO>
