<HEADLINE> Philippine President Issues Orders to Revitalize Mindanao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- President Joseph Estrada Friday
issued a series of orders geared to revitalize Mindanao's economy
by modernizing agriculture and reverse the ongoing food crisis in
the south.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in Davao City in Mindanao, Estrada said that
agricultural modernization is one of his administration's highest
priorities to boost its centerpiece agenda of food security.
</P>
<P>
"Here in Mindanao, in my view, lies the future of our program
on food security, self-sufficiency and self-reliance. We should
develop and strengthen Mindanao because it will bring food to the
table of every Filipino," the president said.
</P>
<P>
Estrada disclosed that in the first half this year, the effects
of El Nino forced the country's agricultural production to drop by
as much as 3.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
"We must address and correct this anomaly with a deep sense of
urgency and concern," he added.
</P>
<P>
Responding to some resolutions presented by the Mindanao
Business Council, Estrada assured that Mindanao will occupy "top
priority in the agriculture and fisheries development program" of
his government.
</P>
<P>
Estrada ordered the Department of Agriculture and other
concerned departments to immediately start identifying strategic
agriculture and fisheries development zones and model farms in
Mindanao, speed up the construction and rehabilitation of rural
infrastructure and establish a research and development fund in
the region.
</P>
<P>
Mindanao's economy plunged to a standstill due to a 24-year war
between government troops and the Moro National Liberation Front
(MNLF) rebels.
</P>
<P>
Although the MNLF signed a final peace pact with the government
in 1996, several other rebel groups are still operating in the
region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
