<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Africa Vows to Meet Deficit Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 7 (Xinhua) -- South African Finance
Minister Trevor Manuel vowed Thursday to meet government's
budgeted deficit target of 3.5 percent of gross domestic product
(GDP) despite the recent economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Addressing Merrill Lynch's investor seminar in Johannesburg
Thursday, Manuel said: "The current (economic) difficulties will
make some of our targets more elusive. But one target that will
not be elusive is the deficit target," Business Day paper
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
There have been doubts that the government would be able to
meet its deficit target as the country's financial markets have
been in turmoil in recent months due to speculative attacks on
the South African currency.
</P>
<P>
The Rand has shed more than a quarter its value against the
U.S. Dollar since the beginning of 1998. The subsequent sharp
rises in interest rates, in a bid to protect the Rand, prompted
predictions that the country's economic growth this year would be
as low as one percent.
</P>
<P>
The government budget for the 98/99 fiscal year projected a
GDP growth of three percent, which was based on the assumption
that banks would allow their historically high interest rates to
drop this year.
</P>
<P>
Manuel said Thursday that despite the changed economic
circumstances, a 3.5 percent deficit remained "entirely
achievable".
</P>
<P>
Low economic growth usually hits government's revenue from
income tax and value added tax, and some economists have
predicted a shortfall of up to two billion Rand (323 million
Dollars) in revenue.
</P>
<P>
But Manuel was optimistic that revenue would hold up. "After
the first few months of the fiscal year, the indications are
positive... The South African revenue service may over-perform
once again."
</P>
<P>
He echoed Reserve Bank governor Chris Stals' optimism about
the current account deficit, predicting it would be below 1.5
percent of GDP this year. At the beginning of the year,
economists predicted two percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the currency crisis, Manuel said the weak Rand
would enhance the country's competitiveness and "the worst of the
shocks" in terms of bad news from South Africa were over. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
