<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China-Unicef Cooperation Goes Smoothly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- China will reach child
development goals by 2000 as scheduled in cooperation with the
United Nations Children's Fund (Unicef), according to Chinese and
Unicef officials.
</P>
<P>
Cooperative programs are being carried out "successfully and
smoothly" in wide-ranging fields, including immunization programs
for children, poverty eradication, lowering mortality rates for
pregnant women and infants, spreading compulsory education and
providing assistance to poverty-stricken children, according to
Vice Minister Sun Zhenyu, from the Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC).
</P>
<P>
Representatives from Unicef's Beijing office and a dozen of
Chinese government departments met here today to review the
partially completed 1996-2000 Program.
</P>
<P>
The program allows the Chinese government to use 145 million US
dollars in Unicef funds to develop health, education and water
supply facilities, as well as to promote social development in
poverty-stricken areas and assist handicapped children.
</P>
<P>
The ministries of health, education, water resources and civil
affairs, and organizations for both women and the handicapped have
joined the program.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation has produced "successful and efficient practices"
related to expanding immunization programs, preventing iodine
deficiency diseases and various other programs, according to
Keshab Mathema, the Unicef representative to China.
</P>
<P>
Chinese and Unicef officials agree that successful cooperation
will help China achieve goals outlined in the National Action
Program for Child Development in China which is scheduled to end
in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The goal of the program is to dramatically reduce the mortality
rate for pregnant women, infants and children under the age of
five, as well as to improve quality of drinking water, promote
compulsory education, eradicate illiteracy, and support programs
in minority, border and poverty-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
Unicef has provided about 300 million US dollars to help
develop China's women's and children's programs since the two
sides restored relations in 1979.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
