<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Stocks Close Weekly Trading Sharply Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong stocks shed 917.79
points, or 11.6 percent, to close the week's trading just above
the 7,000-point mark under the pressure of rising interbank
interest rates, poor corporate results and a weak Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Hang Seng Index closed at 7,018.41 points Friday,
the lowest level for three and a half years.
</P>
<P>
Monday the market tumbled 383.43 points, or 4.83 percent, to
finish at 7,552.77 amid a weaker yen and rising interbank rates.
Trading was jittery before the interim results from banking group
HSBC and revised first-quarter GDP growth figures, both of which
came right after the market closed.
</P>
<P>
Short-covering brought the index modestly higher Tuesday when
the index closed at 7,580.80, up 28.03 points or 0.37 percent.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday an overnight plunge on Wall Street dragged down Hong
Kong stock prices to a six-week low of 7,466.43, with a dip of
114.37 points or 1.51 percent.
</P>
<P>
Thursday rising local interbank rates over fears of a new round
of speculative attacks against the Hong Kong dollar pulled the
index down to 7,254.36 points, the lowest since January 1995.
</P>
<P>
Interbank rates shot higher Friday and the index fell 235.95
points, or 3.25 percent, to close at 7,018.41, a new low for three
and a half years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
