<HEADLINE> Young Inventors Gain Glory in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 7 (Xinhua) -- A grand awarding ceremony was
held here Friday at the Government House to honor some 400 prize
winners in a national youth invention competition.
</P>
<P>
Betty Tung, wife of the Chief Executive of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (SAR), officiated at the prize
presentation ceremony of the Ninth National Science Creation and
Invention Contest for Chinese Young People.
</P>
<P>
After year-long selection and appraisal by an expert team, a
total of 405 inventions and scientific theses, the brain child of
primary and secondary school students, were finally awarded the
prizes.
</P>
<P>
Wang Liping, a 15-year-old girl from east China's Anhui
Province, gain laurels with her invention of a safe folded sickle,
an improved farming instrument. Like Wang, 64 other adolescent
inventors also won the first-rate prize.
</P>
<P>
The second-rate prize went to 148 talented young people, and
the third-rate prize, to 192 teenager inventors. Hong Kong
students won 12 prizes.
</P>
<P>
This year more than 15 million Chinese young people took part
in the youth invention contest, a science education event
organized by China National Leading Group of Science Activities
for Children every two years since 1982.
</P>
<P>
The tenth invention competition will be held in Hefei, the
capital city of Anhui Province two years later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
