<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese PM Not to Visit Yasukuni Shrine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi
said Friday he would not visit Tokyo's Yasukuni Shrine on the 53rd
anniversary of Japan's surrender in World War II.
</P>
<P>
"At the moment, I am not planning to visit the shrine," Obuchi
told reporters at his official residence.
</P>
<P>
Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiromu Nonaka also said he would not visit
the shrine August 15 to avoid stirring criticism from neighboring
countries.
</P>
<P>
Five other cabinet members - Foreign Minister Masahiko Komura,
Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazwa, Education Minister Akito Arima,
International Trade and Industry Minister Kaoru Yosano and
Economic Planning Agency chief Taichi Sakaiya - have also said clearly
that they would not visit the shrine.
</P>
<P>
The Yasukuni Shrine, a bastion of the wartime government-sponsored
Shintoism and symbol of militarism in Japan before and during World
War II, houses the memorial tablets of 14 class-A war criminals,
including wartime Prime Minister Hideki Tojo, and some 2.4 million
Japanese military personnel and officials who have died since 1853 in
Japan's various wars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
