<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 40 People Killed in Nairobi Bomb Blast: Red Cross </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Forty people were killed in the
huge bomb blast which destroyed a building next to the U.S.
Embassy in the commercial area of Nairobi Friday morning, the
International Committee of Red Cross (ICRC) estimated here.
</P>
<P>
Nina Galbe, the ICRC information officer, said about 400
people were injured and the casualty figures were expected to
rise.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of rescue workers were still looking for victims
under the rubble.
</P>
<P>
At least two big buses full of passengers were seriously
damaged as they passed the building when the bomb blew up, the
Kenya Television Network (KTN) reported, adding that most of the
passengers were feared dead.
</P>
<P>
The explosion was suspected to be caused by a car bomb outside
the 26-story Cooperative House on the right of the U.S. embassy.
The building's top three stories had collapsed.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Ambassador Prudence Bushnell was seen to be taken out
into an ambulance vehicle, blood in the face.
</P>
<P>
People were seen hurt and burned and running away in panic
following the bombing.
</P>
<P>
The Cooperative House hosts Kenya's Trade Ministry offices
where it is reported that a meeting between Trade Minister Joseph
Kamotho and Bushnell was held Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
However, the Kenya Television Network (KTN) said at its 1:00
p.m. news broadcasting that the trade minister was not hurt and
has returned to his house safely.
</P>
<P>
Kenya Police spokesman William Changole asked people to
withdraw from the downtown area so as to give space for the
rescue work.
</P>
<P>
It was not immediately clear what is behind the explosion in
Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
Police, ambulances and fire trucks were seen rushing to the
scene and severe traffic jam was formed in downtown and nearby
suburbs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
