<HEADLINE> Nairobi Bomb Casualty Increases to 1,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The casualty figures in the
Nairobi bomb blast has increased to 1,000, the International
Committee of Red Cross (ICRC) said here Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The death toll of the bomb blast Friday morning has been put
at 40.
</P>
<P>
A latest report from the Kenya Television Network said both
U.S. ambassador to Kenya Prudence Bushnell and Kenyan Trade
Minister Joseph Kamotho have sustained slight injuries.
</P>
<P>
A local photographer told Xinhua that 22 people were killed on
the scene and taken directly to the city mortuary and another
four were dead on the road to the Jomo Kenyatta hospital, the
largest in the country.
</P>
<P>
All the main hospitals in Nairobi now are full of the victims,
eye-witnesses told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi has called on people in the
capital city to help with medical facilities.
</P>
<P>
It was widely suspected that terrorists were behind the
explosions which obviously target the U.S. embassies in the
African countries.
</P>
<P>
The bomb blasts in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam are said to be
the first ever of its kind since the two east African countries
gained independence in early 1960s. 
