<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crews Constantly Monitor North Flood Gate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Yu Liangjun has spent the day
constantly checking equipment at the North Flood Gate on the banks
of the Yangtze River to ensure its soundness if the call comes for
the diversion of flood waters.
</P>
<P>
The gate is one of major flood diversion facilities along the
Yangtze in central Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
The gate was built in 1952 and was used for flood water
discharges on three occasions in 1954 when a deadly deluge
devastated central China and killed over 33,000 people.
</P>
<P>
A memorial plaque on the gate commemorates anti-flood efforts
in 1954 in the following inscription penned by Mao Zedong: "Trying
to complete the Jingjiang Flood Diversion Project to protect the
interests of the people."
</P>
<P>
"We will respond to any diversion order by dynamiting the
cofferdams to release flood water," according to Yu.
</P>
<P>
"We conducted a simulation exercise in 1996," said Yu, adding
that routine maintenance has since been carried out to ensure the
normal operation of all equipment. He pointed out that some 80-odd
people work at the gate.
</P>
<P>
Taipingkou Village, home to nearly 3,000 villagers, sits in
close proximity to the gate. Most villagers had been evacuated
since 18:00 on Thursday, with only a skeleton crew remaining to
protect the property of local residents.
</P>
<P>
Livestock has also been moved to higher ground, while small
animals such as ducks and geese have been left to fend for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
"There have been no reports about criminal activities,"
according to a local member of the public security bureau. He
said, "people are abandoning their belongings and moving to safe
areas,"
</P>
<P>
Chinese reporters, the majority of whom work in the Hubei news
media, have flocked to the scene.
</P>
<P>
Hydrometric Patrol Boat No.207 was the only vessel operating
this afternoon in the Yangtze River section near the gate in
Gong'an County, central China's Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
Local hydrometric teams continue to constantly measure water
levels to provide updated reports to flood control departments
which are considering the possibility of dynamiting levees to
divert flood water and protect major.
</P>
<P>
"This section of the channel has doubled the normal width of
1,500 meters," according to one worker.
</P>
<P>
The new flood crest, the fourth of the year, has raised water
levels well beyond the danger level, with water rising 44.81
meters by 19:00 on Friday. Rising water levels have been
accompanied by a flow rate of 47,500 cu.m./second.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary plans for the diversion to be carried out when
water level reaches 45 meters, according to a local official in
charge of flood control.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
