<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese PM Pledges Utmost Efforts to Revive Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi pledged Friday to take "decisive, swift" steps to
revitalize the ailing economy and resolve the bad-loan problems of
Japanese banks as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
"I am determined to do my best at the risk of the cabinet to
put the Japanese economy back on a recovery track in a year or
two," Obuchi, who became prime minister on July 30, said in his
first policy speech at an extraordinary Diet (parliament) session.
</P>
<P>
The best way for Japan to contribute to the rest of Asia and the
world was to put its own financial system in order and revive the
economy, Obuchi said.
</P>
<P>
His government would seek cooperation for the early passage of
bills to stabilize the financial system, including a bridge bank
plan to solve the bad-loan mess of Japanese banks.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to jump-start the economy, Obuchi said the government
would work out a second supplementary budget worth more than 10
trillion yen (about 69.2 billion dollars) for fiscal 1998, which
started April 1.
</P>
<P>
He also pledged to implement "permanent" individual and
corporate tax cuts worth more than six trillion yen (about 41.5
billion dollars) next year.
</P>
<P>
The government intends to lower the highest rate of the
combined national and local individual income taxes to 50 percent
next January from the current 65 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi also said the government would reduce the effective rate
of corporate taxes next April to 40 percent from 46.36 percent in
a bid to enable Japanese companies to compete on an equal footing
with companies in countries with a lower rate.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi said he would freeze the Fiscal Structural Reform Law
"for some time" to stimulate the economy and would seek Diet
approval for the move during its next regular session.
</P>
<P>
The November 1997 law calls for restraints on government
spending to restructure the nation's finances burdened with huge
deficits. It was revised in late May to cope with the economic
setback.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi also expressed his resolve to carry out administrative
reform aimed at reorganizing Japan's existing 22 government
ministries and agencies to 13 by January 2001.
</P>
<P>
Through the reform, deregulation and decentralization, Obuchi
pledged to make "efforts to realize a 20 percent cut in the
regular number of public servants and a 30 percent cut in costs".
</P>
<P>
Turning to foreign policy, Obuchi promised that Japan would
offer "as much assistance as possible" as part of the leadership
role it plans to take in helping Asia countries recover from their
monetary and financial crises.
</P>
<P>
"Japan and China, both bearing responsibilities for the
stability and prosperity of the whole Asia-Pacific region, should
extend their relationship to further develop dialogue and exchange
beyond merely bilateral ties, but with an eye to the international
community," Obuchi said.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi also reconfirmed that Tokyo-Washington ties constitute
the center of Japan's diplomacy and said, "It is of importance to
establish even better and stronger bilateral relations in a wide
variety of fields including security and economy."
</P>
<P>
Referring to Japan's relations with Russia, Obuchi said he
would strive to conclude a peace treaty by the year 2000 by
resolving disputes over four Russian-held islands off Japan's
northernmost main island of Hokkaido.
</P>
<P>
Repeating Tokyo's position that nuclear tests by India and
Pakistan in May cannot be tolerated, Obuchi said Japan "will take
the initiative in maintaining and strengthening the nuclear
nonproliferation regime, promoting nuclear disarmament and
(taking) realistic approaches toward a world free of nuclear
weapons."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
