<HEADLINE> Over 10 Tons of Ammunition Lost in Rains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 7 (Xinhua) -- More than 10 tons of ammunition had
been swept away by floods or landslides caused by torrential rains
in northern Seoul and Kyonggi Province since Wednesday night, the
Defense Ministry said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The ammunition, including mortar shells, flare bombs and
grenades stored in a facility in Songchu, in Kyonggi Province
which surrounds Seoul, was swept into Hantan River and remained
unaccounted for, said a spokesman of the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Some 200 M-14 anti-personnel mines were also swept away by
landslides and floods triggered by the rains, which have left 131
people dead and 61 missing since Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of soldiers are looking for the lost ammunition and
residents in the area should be cautious, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, parts of the U.S. military base in
Uijongbu-Tongduchon area, north of Seoul, were seriously damaged,
and two ammunition storage containers were washed into a river in
Tongduchon, U.S. Forces in South Korea said in a news release
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The containers held grenades and anti-tank mines.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. military is making every effort to recover the
ammunition as soon as possible, said the news release. 
</P>
</TEXT>
