<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Announces Framework for Corporate Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister and Finance Minister Anwar Ibrahim Friday announced the
approach and framework of the Corporate Debt Restructuring
Committee formed to ensure that viable businesses continue to
receive financing for their operations.
</P>
<P>
The measures to be taken by the committee would generate
economic activities and help Malaysia's economic recovery in the
process, Anwar told a press conference here Friday, at which also
present were Anwar's two deputies Affifuddin Omar and Wong See
Wah, Bank Negara (state bank) Deputy Governor Fong Weng Phak and
Securities Commission Chairman Mohd Munir Abdul Majid.
</P>
<P>
The salient features of the committee's approach does not have
any legal status, Anwar said, adding that debt workout will be on
a voluntary basis involving debtors as well as domestic and
foreign creditors.
</P>
<P>
He said the five-member committee will be chaired by the deputy
governor of Bank Negara, with the other members comprising one
representative from the Treasury and three from the private sector
with experience in the legal, accounting and banking fields.
</P>
<P>
The committee will commence operation on August 17 and continue
to operate until the end of 1999 or earlier, which will be decided
by the members themselves.
</P>
<P>
A full-time secretariat will be set up at Bank Negara to assist
the committee, according to Anwar.
</P>
<P>
The approach does not lay down "rules" but general principles
governing how creditors and debtors could conduct themselves in
that workout.
</P>
<P>
Among the principles of debt restructuring is that debt workout
is on a voluntary basis and could be initiated by either the
debtor or creditor and any debt restructuring should be for viable
businesses and decisions should be made based on complete and
accurate information which has been independently verified by an
appointed consultant, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said creditors should agree on a standstill period of 60
days (extendible on special circumstances) so that informed and
orderly decisions could be made.
</P>
<P>
Another rule is that each of the private restructuring process
must be completed expeditiously and within the specified time
frame, he added.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said on the operational side of the committee, there
would be a briefing to the chief executives of banking
institutions especially on the details of the debt restructuring
framework.
</P>
<P>
Corporations may seek the assistance of the committee to
approach the creditors for possible debt restructuring, he said,
adding "Banking institutions may on their own identify
corporations for possible debt workout."
</P>
<P>
In all cases, the corporations which were identified must
fulfill four criteria, which include viable businesses, having
outstanding debt of 50 million ringgit (11.99 million U.S.
dollars) or more, borrowings from more than three creditors, and
not placed under receivership or liquidation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said banking institutions should continue with their own
efforts in debt workouts for their customers which fall outside
this approach and that small borrowers could channel their
requests for assistance to the loan monitoring unit (LMU) at Bank
Negara.
</P>
<P>
The role of LMU includes continuing to assist borrowers who
face difficulties in securing loans from banks and to facilitate
banks to continue to provide financial support to viable
businesses in accordance with the objectives of corporate debt
restructuring.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister said all existing guidelines and rules
including those on the classification of non-performing loans
would continue to be applicable to loans under consideration for
debt restructuring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
