<HEADLINE> China Plans To Cut Coal Production Because Of Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, August 7 (Xinhua) -- China has plans to cut coal
production by at least 200 million tons over the next three years
because of a massive oversupply, according to Wu Yin, the
Deputy-Director of the China Economic and Trade Commission's State
Coal Industry Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Wu told a meeting held in Shanxi Province, China's coal basin,
that this year they estimate cuts of 100 million tons. The bureau
will overhaul township and individual coal mines and in the
three-year period will close down some 22,000 small coal mines.
</P>
<P>
He says that the bureau has put control of key state-owned coal
mines in local hands so that it will give more thought to regional
energy coordination.  
