<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Uses High-Tech Radar to Monitor Flooding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have used the
country's most advanced microwave imaging radar to monitor the
flooding on the Yangtze River, and have provided accurate data for
the disaster-appraisal and anti-flood construction.
</P>
<P>
From July 27 to August 3, four scientists at the Institute of
Electronics under the Chinese Academy of Sciences used airborne
radar to monitor and record the microwave image data of 50,000
square kilometers in central China's Hunan Province and east
China's Jiangxi Province, said Shao Yiming, who headed the group.
</P>
<P>
Shao said it is the first time for the L-Band Synthetic
Aperture Radar (L-SAR), which was developed last year as the first
of its kind in China, to be used for a major state task.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, researchers at both the Institute of Electronics and
the Institute of Remote Sensing Application were working
round-the-clock in Beijing to process and analyze the data sent
back from the two provinces, and report the disaster situation to
the State Flood Control and Drought Relief Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
"The image data obtained by the experts at the Institute of
Electronics through radar is a precious reference for both the
appraisal of the current flooding situation and the construction
of anti-flood facilities to combat such big flooding, which only
comes once every 100 years," said Huang Maoheng, vice-governor of
Jiangxi Province.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that the technique of microwave imaging is
superior to optical and infra-red imaging because it can function
day and night and will not be affected by weather. It also can be
used for harvest predictions, pollution monitoring, resource
survey and ocean studies.
</P>
<P>
The Institute of Electronics began research and development on
microwave imaging radar in 1976. The L-SAR was developed in June
of 1997 by the institute's Engineering Center of Microwave Imaging
Radar System. The radar discovered a part of the ancient Great
Wall underneath sand in northwest China in a flight last year.
</P>
<P>
Since heavy rain began in north China, areas around the Yellow
River and the Haihe River may also be threatened by
flooding. Scientists at the institute are waiting for further
notice from the central government to decide if they should use
radar monitoring in north China's flood areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 11:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- The Yemeni Ministry of Petroleum and Mineral Wealth
anticipates that Yemen will start exporting natural gas by the
year 2003, a delay of two years from the originally schedule, the
Arabic daily Al Hayat reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a report of the ministry as saying that the
marketing of natural gas is the most important aspect for the
implementation and success of the project during the coming years.
</P>
<P>
The report said the first phase of the project which covers the
feasibility studies, designs and surveys has been completed early
this year, and that the execution stage will begin as soon as
contracts of natural gas sales are signed later in the year.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The total volume of the vocational training market in
Saudi Arabia is estimated at 9 billion Saudi rials (240 million
U.S. dollars), Al Hayat reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Deputy General Manager of Saudi Arabia's Al
Charq Plastics factory Sobhi Hashem as saying that the Saudi
vocational training market is the biggest in the Gulf region. It
is expanding by 4 to 6 percent annually in line with the expansion
of the private sector and the high growth of approximately 4
percent in the population of Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- The volume of remittances of Tunisian expatriates
during the past 10 years amounted to some 5 billion dollars
and, statistics published Friday by local daily Al Sabah showed.
</P>
<P>
The amount of such remittances in last year stood at 760
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, about 7 percent of the Tunisian people
live abroad, particularly in western European countries, including
57 percent in France alone. The remittances have contributed to
offset the deficit in Tunisia's balance of payments.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The governor of the Egyptian port city of Port Said
Mustafa Sadeq has disclosed that three new investment projects
will be implemented in the Port Said free zone with joint
Egyptian-Chinese capital of 5 million dollars, the Egyptian daily
Al Ahram reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The projects include a factory for producing radio cassettes,
another for measurement sets, and the third for plastic products.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- An agreement has been signed between Egypt and Eritrea
for the establishment of a permanent exhibition of Egyptian
products in the Eritrean capital city of Asmara, Al Ahram reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed to make use of Eritrean ports and the
new navigation line that passes by Eritrea in transporting
Egyptian products and commodities en route to African states.
</P>
</TEXT>
