<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada said Friday that his administration will cooperate with
the Malaysian government for the release of 22 Filipinos kidnapped
by sea pirates.
</P>
<P>
The Filipinos, crew and passengers of a ship which was missing
four months ago, are reportedly still alive and in the custody of
the kidnappers in a small town bordering Malaysia and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The pirates are allegedly demanding 22 million pesos (523,810
U.S. dollars) as ransom for their release.
</P>
<P>
But Estrada ruled out the payment of ransom to the kidnappers
as he stressed the government's policy of not giving money to
kidnapping gangs in a press conference held in Davao city, the
southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
"The government does not negotiate, neither does it raise
ransom money," Defense Secretary Oriando Mercado said on the same
occasion.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian government said it is ready to cooperate with the
Philippine government in the release of the hostages.
</P>
<P>
The hostages were earlier presumed to have died when their
vessel disappeared on April 4 in the Philippine waters.
</P>
<P>
The remains of the chief mate and engineer were recovered by
fishermen a few weeks after the ship sank. Their bodies bore mark
of torture. 
</P>
