<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rural Children's Health Needs Improvement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Neonatal tetanus, iodine
deficiency and malnutrition are still a threaten to children's
health in rural China, an official with the Ministry of Health
said today.
</P>
<P>
"Disease prevention and treatment remains an arduous task in
rural areas, especially poor areas," Wang Longde, vice-minister of
health, told a conference of the United Nations Children's Fund in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Wang said the most serious diseases of children in those areas
are neonatal tetanus and iodine deficiency, while the incidence of
growth retardation among children under 5 years old has been
lingering above 30 percent in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
Wang said the hygiene problem with water supply and latrines
and the environmental problems as well as the spreading of
Sexually Transmitted Diseases (STDs) and AIDS are challenging the
health of rural children.
</P>
<P>
"This poses a potential risk which could affect the quality of
the future labor force, and in turn hinder the country's economic
development," he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, rural residents often suffer from delayed
care-seeking, which is caused by the underdeveloped economy and
health care, and inadequate knowledge of first aid and basic
health care.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Health Ministry is working on a plan to improve
medical service in rural areas, which includes promoting a basic
medi-care system for farmers, providing basic services to women
and children, and improving medical services in poor areas and in
the areas inhabited by ethnic minorities.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that China is going to hold a national conference on
environmental sanitation, which aims at improving hygiene in rural
areas. The Health Ministry also plans to launch health education
activities in rural areas, with the help of the All-China Women's
Federation and the Ministry of Education.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
