<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Industrial Development Fund Urged in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- A high-powered committee has
proposed the setting up of an industrial development fund with a
view to expediting Bangladesh's industrial sector, a major English
daily reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The committee, headed by Lutfor Rahman Sarkar, governor of
Bangladesh Bank, the central bank of the country, submitted to the
government the proposal last week for approval, The Financial
Express quoted an official source as saying.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was under active consideration of the government
because of the dearth of funds in the banks for long and
medium-term financing, he said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the specialized financing institutions for industrial
financing were facing serious fund crisis because of huge default
loans, he added.
</P>
<P>
There are two specialized financing institutions for industrial
financing, but long and medium-term financing "is almost closed"
in these two banks, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The nationalized commercial banks "are also showing less
interest" in long and medium-term financing because of shortage of
funds resulted from the huge amount of default loans.
</P>
<P>
In its recommendations, the committee said creation of the fund
was necessary for speedy industrial development in the country.
</P>
<P>
Before setting up a permanent structure, the fund could
primarily be regulated by an independent "Industrial Development
Fund Board of Directors" under the Bangladesh Bank, the committee
stated, adding that the fund should be finally be run by a
non-bank investment company, which "will be a government-private
joint venture".
</P>
<P>
The company would finance in both local and foreign currency,
but it would preferably provide and realize loan in foreign
currency to avoid any possible loss by "investment risk".
</P>
<P>
The fund would be created from three sources -- sale proceeds
of foreign currency bonds, fund from the International Finance
Corporation and special funding by the government, the committee
said.
</P>
<P>
The committee also proposed introducing 5, 7 and 10-year term
foreign currency bonds immediately to start collecting resources
for the fund. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
