Thousands of residential houses have become vacant with their
doors widely open as local residents were being evacuated to safe
places for a possible diversion of the rampant flood waters.
</P>
<P>
Many villagers are seen walking solemnly along the roads,
mostly carrying luggages on their back or leading a cattle.
</P>
<P>
Although the flood-control authorities, headed by Vice-Premier
Wen Jiabao, are still pondering on whether to break parts of the
Yangtze dykes for diversion, the evacuation to make way for
possible diversion already started 18:00 pm on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
So far, over 200,000 locals have been relocated by local
government in an organized way. And 130,000 more people are
expected to be resettled in safe places including shelters, safety
platforms and dykes.
</P>
<P>
The Jingjiang Flood Diversion Zone, built in 1952, which is
located in Gong'an County, is designed to divert flood waters to
protect major cities downstream.
</P>
<P>
Local villagers feel quite nervous about the evacuation and the
possible diversion that would flood their dear home.
</P>
<P>
"We did not expect this," a local farmer said, adding that
"because the diversion zone has been used since 1954. But it is
worthwhile doing if needed for saving large cities like Wuhan."
</P>
<P>
The government would compensate for those who sacrifice their
home for the diversion, a local official told Xinhua.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
