<HEADLINE> Indonesian Armed Forces Concerned About Human Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Defense Minister and
Chief of the Indonesian Armed Forces (ABRI) Gen. Wiranto Friday
said the ABRI is concerned about human rights.
</P>
<P>
The ABRI does not keep its eyes off human rights violations in
the country, Wiranto said during a meeting with ulemas and social
figures in Lhokseumawa in the Special Territory of Aceh.
</P>
<P>
He said that human rights are inherent to each human being and
are endowed by God, and the abuse of power to oppress other
people's rights is a tyrannical act which God condemns.
</P>
<P>
"If there are still erring soldiers who have evaded (the law),
we all believe that sooner or later they will get punishment from
God," he was quoted by Antara News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
"As ABRI chief, I sincerely hope for assistance from ulemas and
social figures to help build up the character of soldiers, who are
part of the Aceh community," Wiranto added.
</P>
<P>
According to local press reports, between 1989 when the
country's westernmost special territory was declared a military
operation zone and 1992, about 2,000 people were killed in
military operations. About a thousand more civilians were detained
on suspicion of supporting the Free Aceh Movement.
</P>
<P>
"ABRI must stop treating dissenting civilians like enemies in a
war. And it must do so without delay, or not only will ABRI lose
all credibility, the country and the nation will be placed in
danger of disintegration," warned the Jakarta Post. 
</P>
</TEXT>
