<HEADLINE> Uganda Not Involved in Unrest in Congo (k): </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Uganda was not at all involved
in the recent rebellion in the Democratic Republic of Congo
(DRC), Ugandan President's Press Secretary Hope Kivengere said
Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone interview with Xinhua, Kivengere made the
remarks in response to the reports that President Laurent Kibala
accused Uganda of involvement in the crisis in a recent press
conference.
</P>
<P>
Kivengere said that she was surprised by the newspaper reports
concerning Kabila's accusation.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and the DRC are close neighbors and good friends and
Uganda will surely not in a position to inflame the problem its
neighbor is currently facing, she stressed.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have been cooperating in fighting against
rebels in their border areas and they have achieved a lot in this
aspect.
</P>
<P>
As for Kabila's alleged accusation, Kivengere said that the
Ugandan government is pursuing diplomatic means of solving this
problem, and contacts at different levels are being established.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that on August 2-3, there was an armed
Tutsi-led rebellion in capital Kinshasa, and quickly it spread to
the eastern part of the country, where it shares borders with
Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, the reports said, Kabila allegedly
demanded Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni and Rwandan
Vice-President Paul Kagame to stop from formenting the rebellion
and withdraw from Congolese territory.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's First Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister
Eriya Kategaya said in a statement Thursday that Uganda respects
the territorial integrity of its neighbors and will not interfere
in the internal affairs of any other country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
