<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood-affected People Resettled in Jiangxi Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, August 7 (Xinhua) -- A million flood-stricken people
in east China's Jiangxi Province are now receiving adequate food
and clothing and make-shift shelters, according to Shu Shengyou,
the provincial governor.
</P>
<P>
Cheng Xiumei, 78, of Nanchang, was concerned about her hometown
in Datangping Township of Xinjian County, where more than 3,000
villagers have endured heavy flooding.
</P>
<P>
She organized her relatives and friends in two days to buy 900
kilograms of rice, five cases of pickled mustard vegetables, and
hundreds of articles of clothing. On Aug. 3, her daughter Hu Lihua
delivered the supplies to the township.
</P>
<P>
"We would have collected more relief goods, but my mother
couldn't wait any longer, saying that the affected people would
suffer more otherwise," said Hu.
</P>
<P>
The province has suffered serious flooding since mid-June which
has affected more than a million people, with the total economic
loss estimated at more than 10 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government is trying its best to protect
people's lives and provide sufficient food, clothing and shelter,
as well as medical care, provincial Party secretary Shu Huiguo
said.
</P>
<P>
Health departments have sent 1,600 medical teams to affected
areas, together with pharmaceuticals worth 8 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
In Hukou County, 90-year-old veteran Zhang Tai hurried to the
local Civil Affairs Department and donated 300 yuan for the relief
effort, although his family was also affected. The blind man and
his wife live on his limited pension, his neighbors said.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of families in Changzhou Township of Boyang County
lost everything overnight, and 10 local businesspeople donated
nearly 3,000 articles of clothing and 1,000 kilograms of rice to
the needy.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the province has received more than 58
million yuan worth of donations, and relief materials valued at
more than 37 million yuan, from home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the province has raised more than 200 million yuan
for the effort. By far, it has distributed 101,340 tons of rice,
217,000 tons of emergency food, and other goods.
</P>
<P>
"We are having a stable social order in affected areas, and
people are remaining calm," said Shu Shengyou. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
