<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Finance Minister
Anwar Ibrahim Friday denied rumors that he will resign as finance
minister.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, who is also deputy prime minister, said at a press
conference here that he is firmly in charge of the Finance
Ministry and "there is no basis to rumors" that he will resign as
finance minister.
</P>
<P>
There has been market talk that Anwar may be resigning as
finance minister allegedly following a rift with Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad, according to official media reports.
</P>
<P>
Anwar also told the press conference, "There is no rift between
us (he and Mahathir)...we meet on a daily basis and decisions are
made together."
</P>
<P>
Asked whether the talk of a rift between him and Mahathir would
affect the economy, Anwar said: "If there is no rift in the first
place, I don't think it will affect. But, of course, you cannot
stop people from instigating or discussing or spreading rumors on
uncertainty."
</P>
<P>
He said the Executive Committee of the National Economic Action
Council (NEAC) comprising the prime minister, Special Functions
Minister Tun Daim Zainuddin and himself, met daily to discuss
issues focusing on efforts to achieve economic recovery. 
</P>
