<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Govt Sets Up "Millennium Bug" Buster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has set
up a "millennium bug" buster and ordered all government agencies
to avail of its services to avert a potentially disastrous crash
in their computer systems by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada said in a news release
Friday that he also directed the Technology and Livelihood
Research Center to formulate and provide cost-effective solution
package to the problem especially for government offices.
</P>
<P>
Estrada required all availing government offices to allocate
funds from their existing resources and savings for their
respective solution package in order to render their
computer-based systems millennium compliant by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
He said prior to the establishment of the buster, no specific
plan has been developed, much less implemented, to tackle the
problem pestering computer systems worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Computerized government agencies had been ordered to formulate
year 2000 conversion plans by institutions like the Central Bank,
Securities and Exchange Commission and National Computer Center,
but no definite corrective actions had been undertaken.
</P>
<P>
The millennium bug problem traced its roots four decades ago
when computer technologies established the data in both computer
software and diskettes as a two digit number, such as 98, to save
storage space.
</P>
<P>
According to experts, with the use of two digits, the year 2000
will be stored as "00", which for humans will mean that year, but
computers could read it differently, like 1900, 1800 or even 1700.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
