<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 19 Congolese Ex-Refugees Flee Back to Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 7 (Xinhua)--Nineteen former Congolese
refugees have returned to their previous sanctuary in western
Tanzania in a bid to escape from the fighting between the army
rebels and the forces loyal to President Laurent Kabila of the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Local media reported Friday that the ex-refugees, leaving
Uvira in the eastern part of DRC, arrived in Kigoma in western
Tanzania on Wednesday morning aboard a Tanzanian registered boat,
Mv Let Them Say.
</P>
<P>
The Kigoma Regional Police Commander, Placid Chaka, was quoted
as saying that they have been sheltered at the Kibirizi refugee
holding centre on the shores of Lake Tanganyika.
</P>
<P>
"They are all safe," he said. "The United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) and the Ministry of Home
Affairs (of Tanzania) are screening them to find out whether they
deserve to be accorded the refugee status."
</P>
<P>
Chaka said that the 19 former refugees had been sheltered in
Kigoma before they were voluntarily repatriated this year to the
DRC.
</P>
<P>
Earliy this week, the UNHCR has suspended the repatriation of
Congolese refugees from western Tanzania to the DRC following an
army rebellion in the east part of DRC.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the UNHCR Branch Office in Dar es Salaam said
Wednesday that they are closely monitoring the situation in that
area and have made appropriate preparations for possible new
arrivals of the Congolese refugees.
</P>
<P>
A total of 53,971 Congolese refugees have been voluntarily
repatriated from the UNHCR camps in western Tanzania since the
operation began last September till the end of July.
</P>
<P>
However, the sources said, some 48,000 Congolese refugees
still remain in Tanzania, waiting for repatriation to their home
country.
</P>
<P>
The Congolese refugees have crossed the border to the western
border areas of Tanzania since late 1996, fleeing a civil war
between soldiers led by Laurent Kabila, the current DRC
president, and the Zairean army of former president Mobutu
Sese-seko who died later in exile in Morocco.
</P>
<P>
A UNHCR report says that as of June 30 this year, Tanzania
accommodates a total of 331,538 refugees from neighbouring DRC,
Burundi, Rwanda and Somali.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Central Bank Changes Inflation Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Zambia (BOZ) has revised
its projected target for the reduction of inflation from nine percent
as announced in the 1998 budget to 15 percent by the end of this year
and the GDP to four percent from 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
This has been necessitated by a number of dynamic issues in
the Zambian economy and some regulations that will need to be put
in place, said Flix Kani, director of the Economics Department at
the central bank.
</P>
<P>
Some of the major causes to the failure to achieve the desired
targets include the decline of the country's agricultural output
due to the EL Nino phenomenon, a report of Zambia Daily Mail said
Friday,
</P>
<P>
The delayed privatization of the remaining mines of the Zambia
Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM) and the withholding of the
balance of payment support by donors are also attributed to the
failure.
</P>
<P>
Zambia spent 40 million U.S. Dollars to import food last year.
And this year more food will be imported to ease the country's
food shortage.
</P>
<P>
Government officials disclosed that the Zambian government
tried every means to lobby worldwide for the sale of its Nkana
and Nchanga mines, which represent 65 percent of the country's
copper output, but no potential buyers have showed serious
interest in buying them till now.
</P>
<P>
However, the completion of privatizing all the ZCCM mines is a
precondition set at a consultative meeting between the Zambian
government and its western donors in Paris last May to release a
pledged aid of 530 million U.S. Dollars to Zambia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
