<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: U.S.-Philippine War Games Arouse Debates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- American and Philippine warships
and aircraft staged live-fire war games in the South China Sea
earlier this week, and this has aroused fierce debates in the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
According to a Philippine navy spokesman, the 18-hour military
exercises were held "outside the Philippine territorial waters"
Wednesday because of the absence of a bilateral agreement
governing such maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
However, the exercises have aroused intense debates in the
country, especially in the Senate, which is under pressure for the
ratification of the controversial Visiting Forces Agreement (VFA).
</P>
<P>
The VFA, which was signed by Philippine Foreign Secretary
Domingo Siazon and U.S. Ambassador Thomas Hubbard in February,
allows the resumption of military exercises between the two
countries and opens the Philippines' 22 ports to the U.S.
military.
</P>
<P>
Washington halted all joint exercises in the Philippines and
visits by U.S. military ships in December 1996 when Manila ended a
legal loophole that had shielded U.S. military personnel from
prosecution by the Philippines for crimes committed in the island
country.
</P>
<P>
Critics say the accord limited the Philippine government's
right to prosecute American soldiers who commit crimes, as it
gives the U.S. jurisdiction over soldiers who commit crimes while
on duty, and the Philippine jurisdiction over crimes committed
while off-duty.
</P>
<P>
Because of the controversies, the Philippine Senate has not yet
begun deliberations on the VFA.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said that by conducting such war games,
Washington and Manila are trying to push the Senate for an early
ratification of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
But some senators questioned the legality of the war games
since the exercises were staged without the VFA, while some
activists described the war games as part of the U.S. government's
program to "hard-sell" the VFA by creating an atmosphere of
discord with the Philippines' neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Senator Raul Roco said that the Philippine Constitution
stipulates that after the expiration of the Philippine-U.S.
Military Base Agreement in the early 1990s, foreign military
troops will not be allowed in the country except under a treaty
concurred in by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Senator Rodolfo Biazon questioned the motive
behind the war games as the exercise was held when Washington is
seeking the early approval of the VFA.
</P>
<P>
"Are these part of the friendly persuasion efforts of the VFA?"
he asked.
</P>
<P>
Military ties with the United States have remained a sensitive
issue in the Philippines since the Philippine Senate forced the
closure of the last U.S. base in the country in 1992, ending
nearly a century of U.S. military presence in its former colony.
</P>
<P>
Senator Aquilino Pimentel said that the VFA provision on
criminal jurisdiction was an attempt by the Americans to foist an
"anachronistic" rule of 1950s vintage.
</P>
<P>
Other senators accused President Joseph Estrada of lobbying for
the Senate's ratification of the agreement by approving the war
games.
</P>
<P>
However, President Estrada said Thursday that he and Defense
Secretary Orlando Mercado were not informed ahead of the war
games.
</P>
<P>
He said that navy and air force officials will be asked to
explain why they did not inform the country's top officials of the
military exercises.
</P>
<P>
He said that the exercises were scheduled during the
administration of his predecessor, Fidel Ramos, who stepped down
on June 30.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, one of the 12 senators who had voted in 1991 against
the continued stay of U.S. military base in the country, said that
he is not stampeding the senators into approving the VFA, and will
respect the Senate's decision.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, he reiterated his defense of the VFA and his
support for the ratification, saying it could enhance the
country's security.
</P>
<P>
Although both the government and the military denied the
linkage between the VFA and the war games, observers said the
exercises were part of their efforts to push for the early
ratification of the VFA.
</P>
<P>
The World News newspaper said in a commentary Friday that
Washington is so anxious for the ratification of the VFA that it
conducted such war games to promote the approval of the agreement
by the Philippine Senate.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: China Seeks Closer Ties in Caribbean, Latin America (1) by Xinhua Writer Liu Yunfei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- While enhancing relations with
other countries, China has intensified its diplomatic efforts to
strengthen links with countries in Latin America and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
Ties between China and that region were cemented by a visit of
Chinese Vice-Premier Qian Qichen to five Caribbean nations late
last month: Barbados, Guyana, Trinidad and Tobago, Cuba and
Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
Qian described the trip as "being positive and achieving
anticipated objectives."
</P>
<P>
An unofficial Chinese delegation has also been visiting the
Caribbean where non-governmental celebrities from both sides
discussed how to foster Sino-Caribbean friendship for the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
The Caribbean island nations belong to many Latin American
associations and are often politically linked with South America.
</P>
<P>
During the discussion early this month at a seminar in
Kingston, Jamaica, the first in nearly 50 years, participants from
17 countries expressed a willingness to facilitate friendship and
cooperation between China and the Latin American-Caribbean region.
</P>
<P>
"It is quite rarely seen in China's diplomatic work in recent
years that official action, together with unofficial exchanges,
have been put in motion almost simultaneously," a local observer
said.
</P>
<P>
He called it a "clear exhibition" of the interest and desire of
both sides to expand their ties.
</P>
<P>
Qian said during his visit that China is willing to bring a
stable Sino-Caribbean relationship into the 21st century based on
equality, mutual support and expanding cooperation.
</P>
<P>
There have been frequent high-level exchange of visits between
leaders of China and the region since the beginning of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Chinese leaders have become acquainted with many Latin American
leaders from north to south in the region.
</P>
<P>
In addition, China has engaged in several dialogues with the
Rio Group, the largest organization for political coordination in
Latin America which includes Caribbean nations in an observer
status.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
