<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: China Seeks Closer Ties with Caribbean, Latin America (2) by Xinhua Writer Liu Yunfei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"These fully show the shared interests of the two sides," said
Xu Shicheng, a professor at the Institute of Latin American
Studies under the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
He said that there is no impending issue between China and
Latin America, thus laying a sound foundation for the growth of
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
"There are many kinds of rich natural resources in Latin
America like oil and iron ore, and Chinese investment is welcome
to Latin America to be involved in natural resource exploitation,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Carlos Moneta, permanent secretary of the Latin American
Economic System, said there is great potential for economic and
trade cooperation between Latin America and China.
</P>
<P>
He added that better understanding of each other will enable
both sides to achieve a "breakthrough" in this area.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade volume with Latin America in the first five
months reached nearly 3 billion U.S. dollars, an increase of 12.4
percent over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
China has so far launched more than 200 solely invested
enterprises or joint ventures in Latin America. It also became an
official member of the Caribbean Development Bank in January of
1998.
</P>
<P>
Although Sino-Latin American relations have been developing
well, analysts said, some barriers in bilateral relationships need
to be removed.
</P>
<P>
They said the main problem in bilateral relationships is that a
small number of countries in the region have no diplomatic
relations with China because of the Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
Qian clearly stated in his Caribbean tour that the Chinese
government is prepared to set up and develop normal state-to-state
relations with those countries.
</P>
<P>
The Bahamas and St. Lucia, both in the Caribbean, established
diplomatic relations with China last year.
</P>
<P>
"St. Lucia has proceeded in a direction which the majority of
the states of the world have already trod by establishing
diplomatic links with the People's Republic of China," said
St. Lucia's Prime Minister Kenny Anthony.
</P>
<P>
A new relationship featuring mutual trust politically, more
economic cooperation and mutual support in the international arena
appear to be the common objectives of the two sides.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
