<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Dollar Appears to Be Stabilizing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The troubled Zimbabwe Dollar
appears to be stabilizing after a heavy bashing against other
currencies early this week, the daily Herald newspaper reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Banks Thursday were buying U.S. Dollars at an average rate of
20 Zimbabwean Dollars and selling them for 22.5 Zimbabwe
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers interviewed Thursday said that more exporters were
off-loading their foreign receipts, bringing the much-needed
liquidity to the market while only importers with payment
commitments were demanding foreign currency.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe Dollar came under heavy import pressure early
this week as panic-gripped importers rushed to buy foreign
currency, creating a shortage on the market.
</P>
<P>
At one stage, 28 Zimbabwean Dollars were tading one U.S.
Dollar before the country's central bank, Reserve Bank of
Zimbabwe, the central bank, took a corrective measure by raising
the rediscount rate -- the rate at which banks borrow -- from
31.5 percent to 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the Zimbabwe Dollar is stabilizing with
suggestions that it was overvalued and the market is
correcting the anomaly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
