<HEADLINE> U.S. Trains Sri Lankan Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The United States has offered
advanced anti-terrorist training for Sri Lankan police to face the
growing challenges in operations against Tamil rebels, according
to the Island newspaper here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The training is organized through the Anti-Terrorist Assistant
Program (ATAP) of the State Department, an authoritative
spokesperson for the U.S. Information Service told the Island
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen officers and men have come to Sri Lanka. They have been
selected to train in the art of defusing different types of
explosive devices, the spokesperson was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The six-week-long course will help Sri Lankan police improve
its capabilities, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-four other officers and men have commenced a 3-week
course aimed at enhancing police capability to protect vital
installations.
</P>
<P>
The course has also been aimed at improving and expanding
ongoing police operations against the Tamil rebels' attempts to
target vital installations in Colombo and provincial towns, the
reports added.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. increased ties with Sri Lankan military in 1995. Since
then Sri Lankan government forces have been given advanced
training conducted through the U.S. Pacific Command. 
</P>
