<HEADLINE> Henan Sets Bottom Line for Poor University Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, August 7 (Xinhua) -- University students who have
difficulty continuing their education in central China's Henan
Province will receive a monthly subsidy from the provincial
government for the coming semester.
</P>
<P>
The project, guided by the provincial Education Bureau, will
provide 120 yuan (around 15 U.S. dollars) to each poor student
every month.
</P>
<P>
Henan, which has the largest population in China, has more than
50 universities of 130,000 students. About 80 percent of the
students come from relatively impoverished rural areas. Some of
them can hardly subsist, which affects their schooling and health.
</P>
<P>
The bottom-line subsidies will be allocated to 5,000 poor
students. In addition, related students will also receive
scholarships, loans and other kinds of financial aid. 
</P>
