<HEADLINE> Turkish Mayor Kidnapped by Kurdish Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- A Turkish mayor, along with
three other people, has been kidnapped by a group of Kurdish
militants in southeastern Turkey, the Daily News newspaper
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The car of Naci Orhan, mayor of Bahcesaray city in the
province of Van, was stopped by rebels of the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK) on a road outside Bahcesaray Wednesday
night. Orhan and three others were abducted by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
A large-scale operation has been launched by the security
forces to find the kidnapped official in the nearby areas. Two
PKK militants were killed in an exchange of fire with the
troops.
</P>
<P>
The incident came shortly after the Emergency Rule Region
Office issued a statement saying that 165 PKK rebels had been
killed over the past week.
</P>
<P>
Local media reported that a group of PKK militants attacked a
military post in southeastern Turkey early this week, killing 15
Turkish soldiers and kidnapping 10 others. But this was not
confirmed by officials.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a guerilla war since 1984 to
establish an independent Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey, in
which over 35,000 people have been killed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
