<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Heart Failure Death Rate Down Between 1988-1995 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 6 (Xinhua) -- A study released Thursday
said that the death rate due to heart failure among U.S. adults
has been declining since 1988.
</P>
<P>
The study by the Federal Center for Disease Control and
Prevention (CDCP) said that the heart failure death rate has
fallen roughly one percent per year between 1988 and 1995, with
the largest average annual decline in black men (3 percent),
followed by black women (2.2 percent), white men (1.7 percent) and
white women (0.5 percent).
</P>
<P>
Other figures in the study showed that in 1988 heart failure
killed 117 per 100,000 people aged 65 or above. In 1995, the last
year for which statistics were available, heart failure killed 108
per 100,000 people over the age of 65, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Experts credited drugs introduced in the late 1980s, called
angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) inhibitors, in part for the
decline of death rate between 1988 and 1995. They also credited
improved tracking by doctors of high-risk individuals and early
intervention after heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
The study particularly pointed out that the sharper decline of
death rate among blacks seen in the 1995 figures may be because of
better access to medical care and improved control of high blood
pressure.
</P>
<P>
Reducing fat and salt intake, maintaining a proper weight,
quitting smoking and exercising can help prevent both hypertension
and heart attack, thus reducing the risk of heart failure, the
CDCP study recommanded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 08:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Central Bank Slashes Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Central Bank has
decided to slash its key lending rates by 1.5 percentage, local
daily The Jerusalem Post reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The report said following the change, which will take effect
on Sunday, the key lending rates will be 9.5 percent, the lowest
level since November 1993.
</P>
<P>
The move was part of a package deal worked out by Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, Finance Minister Yaakov Neeman and
Bank of Israel Governor Jacob Frenkel over the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The other elements of the deal, which was aimed at spurring
the economic growth, included setting next year's inflation
target at 4 percent and a technical change to the exchange rate
mechanism of foreign currencies.
</P>
<P>
And before Frenkel formally announced the cut of the interest
rates on Thursday, the Finance Ministry also presented its 1999
budget to the cabinet the same day.
</P>
<P>
The ministry predicted that this year's economic growth will be
1.5 percent, its lowest this decade, but it could rebounce to 2.5
percent in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
