<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Wool Prices Plunge to Four-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Australian wool prices plunged
to a four-year low this week amid confusion over the future of the
country's massive 1.1 million bale (80.57 million kg) wool
stockpile.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Wool Exchange (AWEX) said Friday its eastern
market indicator fell 44 Australian cents to 549 Australian cents
(329 U.S. cents) per kg clean when sales resumed in Sydney,
Melbourne and Fremantle after a three-week break.
</P>
<P>
A total of 103,086 bales were offered, with 28.4 percent passed
in.
</P>
<P>
"The industry debate of recent weeks over stockpile disposal
arrangements added an additional negative factor into what was
always going to be a difficult market environment this week," AWEX
said.
</P>
<P>
"Continuing subdued market consumer demand, the traditional
European holiday period, and an extremely large offering of
growers' wool by today's standards provided the basic
ingredients," it added.
</P>
<P>
The Australian government Tuesday announced a freeze on all
sales from the nation's 1.1 million bale wool stockpile for 12
months in a bid to spur on low prices.
</P>
<P>
AWEX said buyers reported little new business in the market.
</P>
<P>
Sales will continue next week in three Australian cities:
Sydney, Adelaide and Fremantle, with 81,000 bales rostered for
sale. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
