<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiangsu Farmers Register Trademark for Jindun Watermelons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, August 7 (Xinhua)-- This summer watermelons with a
special trademark "Jindun" sell very well on the market in the
East China region in spite of the price decline caused by a bumper
harvest.
</P>
<P>
Jindun watermelons, grown in Jindun Town of Dafeng City in East
China's Jiangsu Province, sell for 0.5-to-1 yuan per kilogram,
much higher than the average price of 0.3-to-0.4 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Qiu Hefei, a farmer of Rennan Village of Jindun Town, said: "I
have planted watermelons for years, but never have had such a good
sale. One watermelon can earn twice as much as before, because we
have registered a trademark for our melons."
</P>
<P>
Jindun Town is noted for its watermelons in the East China
region which includes Shanghai, Nanjing and Suzhou. But in recent
years some watermelons from other parts of the country, falsely
labeled as Jindun melons, were sold on the market.
</P>
<P>
In March of this year, the melon growers of Jindun Town set up
a watermelon association under the local government. They applied
for the "Jindun" trademark to the administration in charge of
trademarks in the country and printed 100,000 trademarks to stick
on their melons.
</P>
<P>
The watermelons with trademarks caught the consumers' attention
soon after their appearance on the market.
</P>
<P>
Many people turned to Jindun melons and, in Shanghai and
Nanjing, the supply has fallen short of demand.
</P>
<P>
Qiu Hefei has printed many namecards which have his name and
address as well as the advertisement on his melons. While selling
the watermelons, he presents the namecards to customers to add to
the popularity of the trademark.
</P>
<P>
An official in charge of industry and commerce in Jiangsu
Province said: "It is a good thing that the farmers registered a
trademark for watermelons. It shows that Chinese farmers have
begun to use the economic laws and regulations to protect their
interests."
</P>
<P>
He added that it was only in recent years that Chinese farmers
began to register trademarks for their products such as grain,
fruits, vegetables and aquatic products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
