<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Breed Sheep With 20-Year-Old Semen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have recently
bred 33 sheep by using 20-year-old frozen semen in northwest
China's Xinjiang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Researchers at the Xinjiang Academy of Animal Husbandry
Sciences began the experiment in 1995, using semen collected from
two Australian sheep in 1975.
</P>
<P>
After thawing the semen, scientists used an endoscope to infuse
the semen into the wombs of 69 sheep. Of these, 28 became pregnant
and eventually gave birth to 33 lambs.
</P>
<P>
The artificially bred sheep, now living on a farm in Urumqi,
capital of Xinjiang, are three years old and look exactly like
their Australian fathers of 20 years ago, said scientists.
</P>
<P>
Each of the sheep weighs more than 100 kg and produces 6.85
kg of wool a year.
</P>
<P>
Although the 20-year-old frozen semen had lost much of its
vitality, the utilization of the endoscope method increased the
conception rate, according to Shi Meiying, a researcher at the
academy.
</P>
<P>
Frozen semen has been used to preserve endangered animals,
however the problem of maintaining the frozen semen's vitality has
yet to be solved.
</P>
<P>
The experiment by the Xinjiang scientists has contributed
greatly to this field of research, according to experts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shandong Increasing Investment in Highway Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, August 7 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province will
spend 72 billion yuan on highway construction during the next five
years, Vice Governor Han Yuqun announced here recently.
</P>
<P>
Most of this money will go to 34 key projects, and upon their
completion in 2002 the total highway mileage in Shandong will
reach 75,000 kilometers, 26,000 of which will be expressways.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the 19 new or ongoing projects will cost an
estimated 9.6 billion yuan this year, 60 percent more than
originally planned, Han said.
</P>
<P>
These projects will provide new jobs for 190,000 people and add
3.9 billion yuan to gross domestic product. As a major economic
powerhouse in east China, Shandong is striving to achieve a GDP
growth rate of nine percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Fueled by the heavy demand for investment, the GDP of this
coastal province grew by 10.3 percent in the first half this year
compared with a year ago. The provincial government plans to raise
investments to 221 billion yuan this year, 23 percent more than
last year.
</P>
<P>
Shandong has been one of the five fastest-growing provinces in
China since the 1980s, and its GDP reached 665 billion yuan last
year, ranking third in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
