<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2,400 Tangshan Paraplegics Survive 22 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Over 2,400 paraplegic people
in Tangshan City in north China's Hebei Province have been
surviving for the 22 years since a major earthquake struck the
city and claimed more than 240,000 lives in 1976.
</P>
<P>
Many overseas medical authorities believed that these victims
could be expected to survive for only 20 years.
</P>
<P>
The 1976 Tangshan quake also injured 420,000 people while
leaving 3,810 paraplegics.
</P>
<P>
To arrange for the rehabilitation of the paraplegic, the city
established 18 rehabilitation centers, and some enterprises also
opened facilities for paraplegic workers.
</P>
<P>
After completing their special training, nearly all of the
paraplegic people are now able to either partially or
completely take care of themselves.
</P>
<P>
Tangshan also built a wheelchair-accessible rehabilitation
village, where more than 40 paraplegic couples have settled.
</P>
<P>
The annual death rate among those left paraplegic by the
earthquake has stood at only 1.64 percent.
</P>
<P>
The city also opened several factories and shops where the
handicapped and paraplegic people have been employed.
</P>
<P>
They engage in occupations such as electrical applicance
maintenance, keymaking, photography, and artistic creation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0194 </DOCNO>
