<P>
 exports
</P>
<P>
 new delhi, aug 7 (pti) the export incentive package
unveiled by indian government is insufficient and will provide
only a marginal impetus for exports growth, director general
national council for economic research (ncaer) rakesh mohan
has said.
</P>
<P>
 the incentive package will no doubt improve the
competitiveness of exports by way of reducing the financing
costs and releasing funds blocked in duty drawback within a
time frame. but this alone is not sufficient, he told pti in
an interview.
</P>
<P>
 mohan said more efforts have to be undertaken by the
exporting community through better internal management of
resources and quality control.
</P>
<P>
 +while the package does come as a relief, any turnaround
in exports performance at this juncture would not be enough to
achieve the targetted 20 per cent growth for 1998-99,+ he
added.
</P>
<P>
 exports dipped by 7.9 per cent in the first quarter of
1998-99 and the trade deficit widened to 2.4 billion dollars
reflecting a slide in the fortunes of exporters.
</P>
<P>
 heeding to the complaints of exporters that high cost of
finance was the biggest factor for slow down in exports,
government reduced the interest rates on pre and post-shipment
credits from 11 per cent to 9 per cent as part of its package
for exporters on wednesday. pti aml aa pti
