<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spokesman on Chinese Ambassador's Refusal to Attend U.S. Hearing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Ministry spokesman Tang
Guoqiang issued a statement today on Li Zhaoxing's refusal to
appear at a U.S. congressional hearing.
</P>
<P>
Li, Chinaese ambassador to the United States, refused to attend
a hearing organized by the International Operations and Human
Rights Subcommittee of the International Relations Committee of
the U.S. House of Representatives on the human rights situation in
China.
</P>
<P>
Tang said the Chinese side is willing to have a dialogue on
human rights on the basis of equality and mutual respect. "China,
however, always opposes any attempt to interfere in its internal
affairs under the pretext of human rights," he said, adding that
such a stance is "clear and consistent."
</P>
<P>
China's embassy in the United States has already issued a
statement on the matter, Tang said.
</P>
<P>
Li accepted the invitation for a meeting on human rights with
members of the subcommittee "in the spirit of openness and
promoting mutual understanding," the statement said. However, Li
had never agreed to serve as a witness before the subcommittee and
"it is not appropriate for the ambassador to appear as a witness
before the congressional subcommittee" in keeping with general
diplomatic practice, it stated.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the statement indicated that Li always welcomes an
opportunity for a genuine and candid dialogue on human rights
issues with members of the U.S. Congress "on an equal footing and
in a manner acceptable to all." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
