<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Situation on Line of Control Takes  Alarming, Worrisome Turn  by Xu Yuenai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Clouds of war are blotting out
on the Line of Control (LoC) as the rival armies of Pakistan and
India are engaged in their worst kind of cross-border artillery
duel in the disputed Kashmir region.
</P>
<P>
Hours after the prime ministers of Pakistan and India came out
of their meeting in Colombo, Sri Lanka, at the end of last month
without breaking a deadlock in the much-awaited official talks,
the armies of the two South Asian nations traded heavy fire along
LoC which, Pakistan blamed, has been triggered by "unprovoked
shelling" by the Indian army.
</P>
<P>
According to a spokesman from Pakistan's Foreign Ministry, more
than 50 civilians have been killed and hundreds of others injured
in Pakistan-held Kashmir area during the last week as a result of
"India's unprovoked and indiscriminate firing across LoC which
separates the disputed region.
</P>
<P>
The armies of the two rival neighbors, positioned eye ball to
eye ball, are reported to be using weapons ranging from mortars to
heavy and light machine guns in the clashes which, according to
estimates by the media, have displaced about 20,000 people from
the bordering villages on the Pakistani side.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government has apprised the United Nations and
the international community of the danger the Indian belligerency
poses to the overall peace and security of the region. It has also
warned that the conflict could escalate into a full-fledged war
which neither country can afford, especially after the induction
of the nuclear factor.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and India, which conducted a series of tit-for-tat
nuclear tests in May, have fought three wars mainly over Kashmir
since their independence from British colonial rule in 1947.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has always called for a U.N.-sponsored plebiscite to
decide the fate of the Muslim-dominated region. However, India
claims Kashmir as its integral part.
</P>
<P>
India blames Pakistan for abetting about 10-year-old insurgency
in its part of kashmir, which Pakistan firmly denies. Islamabad
says it only extends political, moral and diplomatic support to
the "Kashmir freedom struggle."
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that skirmishes between the rival armies
at LoC take place quite often in the disputed region. But tension
mounted between the two estranged neighbors following their
nuclear tests at the end of May.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman from Pakistan's Foreign Ministry, while describing
the situation as "precarious" along the LoC, said that "there is
a limit" to its (Pakistan's) patience.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Indian Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee in a
recent address at the Parliament vowed a firm response to Pakistan
in case of attack on India.
</P>
<P>
"We are committed to keeping our borders secure. We will deal
with a firm hand any attack by Pakistan," local newspapers quoted
Vajpayee as saying.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and India have had several rounds of talks at various
levels in the past. However, sharp differences over the Kashmir
dispute always led to breakdown.
</P>
<P>
Foreign secretaries of the two countries held three rounds of
talks since the government of Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif took
power in February 1997.  The top diplomats of the countries
reached an agreement in Islamabad in June last year charting up an
eight-point priority agenda with peace and security, and Kashmir
topping the list.
</P>
<P>
Differences cropped over the mechanism as to how to deal with
the Kashmir issue. While Islamabad insists that the Kashmir
dispute stands out in the bilateral talks, New Delhi wants the
discussion over the dispute to be part of a "composite process,"
covering all outstanding issues between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the Kashmir issue still stands as the main
obstacle for Pakistan and India to normalize their strained
relations. And the warmongering on LoC is, by any means, not
helpful to the peaceful solution of the Kashmir dispute and
certainly contrary to the wishes of the two peoples.
competitiveness of exports by way of reducing the financing
costs and releasing funds blocked in duty drawback within a
time frame. but this alone is not sufficient, he told pti in
an interview.
</P>
<P>
 mohan said more efforts have to be undertaken by the
exporting community through better internal management of
resources and quality control.
</P>
<P>
 +while the package does come as a relief, any turnaround
in exports performance at this juncture would not be enough to
achieve the targetted 20 per cent growth for 1998-99,+ he
added.
</P>
<P>
 exports dipped by 7.9 per cent in the first quarter of
1998-99 and the trade deficit widened to 2.4 billion dollars
reflecting a slide in the fortunes of exporters.
</P>
<P>
 heeding to the complaints of exporters that high cost of
finance was the biggest factor for slow down in exports,
government reduced the interest rates on pre and post-shipment
credits from 11 per cent to 9 per cent as part of its package
for exporters on wednesday. pti aml aa pti
