<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nature Reserve Becomes Home to White Storks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, August 7 (Xinhua) -- More than 200 white storks have
become the "pride and symbol" of the Honghe Marshland Nature
Reserve in northeast China's Heilongjiang Province, a technician
of the nature reserve said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhu Baoguang, the technician with the reserve,
these nearly one-meter-tall birds live in the reserve 300
kilometers east of Jiamusi, a medium-sized less polluted city in
the province, from April through October every year to propagate
baby storks, and then leave the region to spend the winter in
southern China.
</P>
<P>
There are now some 1,000 white storks in the country, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
Built in 1984, the Honghe Marshland Nature Reserve with a range
of 20,000 hectares is a national nature reserve and home to more
than 190 species of animals and nearly 1,000 kinds of plants,
according to Zhu.
</P>
<P>
What has attracted such a big number of white storks is the
region's large area of marshland and great variety of fish,
necessary living conditions and food for waterfowl, birds
specialists say.
</P>
<P>
Manmade nests are another factor attracting white storks, Zhu
added.
</P>
<P>
Zhu explained that between 1984 and 1992, fewer than six white
storks lived in the reserve, and the number of storks has been on
the rise since 1993 when Zhu and his colleagues started building
nests.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
