<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scholars Extract DNA From Ancient Rice Seed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Scholars at China Agricultural
University have successfully extracted DNA from 5,500-year-old
single-grain carbonized rice seeds.
</P>
<P>
It is believed to be the first time for scientists in the world
to extract DNA from ancient plants aging more than 5,000 years.
</P>
<P>
Professor Wang Xiangkun, Associate Professor Sun Chuanqing, and
Li Chen, a postgraduate student at the university, went on to
conduct the external expansion of the DNA (to increase the amount
of related DNA parts), and hybridized them with the genome DNA of
"Yuefu," a kind of modern japonica rice.
</P>
<P>
The outcome made it clear that the expanded parts are of the
DNA of the ancient rice.
</P>
<P>
The ancient single-grain carbonized rice was unearthed from the
relic site of Longqiu Village of Gaoyou City in East China's
Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
The extraction and expansion of its DNA provided a new way for
the research of the origin and evolution of Asian cultivated rice,
the scholars said. It is also important for the differentiation
from the ancient cultivated rice to wild rice, the ancient indice
rice to japonica rice and for the foundation of the molecular
archeology.
</P>
<P>
According to experts, scientists in the world have never before
extracted DNA from plants more than 3,200 years old.
</P>
<P>
The scholars at the university are comparing the DNA molecules
of the modern rice with ancient rice in different periods of time
to further understand the variation of the DNA molecules of the
cultivated rice in the process of evolution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
