<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floods Challenging China's Anti-Poverty Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Continuing floods along the
Yangtze River will make China's goal of helping 10 million people
out of poverty this year more difficult to reach, a government
official said today.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics show that by August 3, a total of 240 million
people in 28 provinces across the country have been affected by
the floods which began in June.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Office of the Leading Group of Poverty
Alleviation and Development under the State Council has pointed
out that most of the flood-stricken areas are state-designated
poverty counties.
</P>
<P>
In east China's Jiangxi Province, for example, the Yangtze
floods have hit all the 18 state-designated poverty counties. The
local government has predicted that the floods will bring more
than one million people in the province down below the poverty
line.
</P>
<P>
The flooding has also slowed or ended many of the
aid-the-poor projects.
</P>
<P>
Families with per capita incomes of less than 300 yuan by 1990
standards are considered poor in China. By the end of 1997, the
country had had 50 million such poor people.
</P>
<P>
Along with the floods, the anti-poverty campaign also faces
other obstacles such as declining prices for farm produce, which
greatly affects the effort to increase farmers' income.
</P>
<P>
The slowing growth rate of township enterprises and the
increasing number of layoffs in urban areas are also decreasing
job opportunities for farmers.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that in the first half of this year the per
capita income of farmers remained at the 1997 level.
</P>
<P>
The reshuffling of governmental departments also delayed the
payment of poverty-relief funds, the official said.
</P>
<P>
To solve these problems, the government plans to adopt measures
ensuring the timely payment of these funds, and the central
government will invest 18 billion yuan this year in this
effort. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0231 </DOCNO>
