<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stern Labels NBA Union Talks Disappointing, Insulting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The first serious collective
bargaining session since the NBA locked out players over a month
ago began smoothly today, but later dissolved into an unproductive
meeting with owners and executives walking out on the Players
Association.
</P>
<P>
After a morning session at a New York law office, the union
returned with a counterproposal and what NBA boss described as
a"lecture" from Players Association attorney Jeffrey Kessler.
</P>
<P>
"The words they were using were insulting, patronizing," NBA
commissioner David Stern said. "We thought it was the better part
of valor to end the discussion."
</P>
<P>
NBA deputy commissioner Russ Granik said:"The players were not
really interested in doing any serious bargaining at this time."
</P>
<P>
Utah Jazz superstar Karl Malone called the exit by Stern,
Granik and a handful of owners "unbelievable. It was like a
4-year-old taking his toys away from the other kids and going
home."
</P>
<P>
No further talks were scheduled, and with the union threatening
legal action, the chance of 1998-99 season starting on time
appears further reduced.
</P>
<P>
The four-year proposal from owners included a guaranteed jump
of at least 50 million U.S. dollars per year in total player
salaries,which last season was just under 1 billion dollars. But
it also included the phasing out over a period of two to three
years of the Larry Bird Exception, which would change the system
from a soft cap to a hard cap.
</P>
<P>
The counterporposal from the union included the Larry Bird
Exception a handful of new salary exceptions.
</P>
<P>
Owners and players signed a six-year agreement in 1996 calling
for the percentage of basketball-related income devoted to
salaries to be 48 percent, with owners given the option to re-open
the agreement if the number climbed above 51.8 percent in the
1997-98 season, salaries totaled 995 million or 57 percent.
</P>
<P>
Claiming up to 15 teams lost money during the season, owners
voted 27-2 in March to re-open the agreement and locked out
players on July 1st. The union says just four teams operated in
the red.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting was attended by 14 players and six owners. Both
sides entered somewhat entrenched position, but there was positive
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The 1998-99 season is the first under the new four-year, 2.64
billion U.S. dollars TV deal that guarantees each owner 23 million
in revenue whether or not games are played.
</P>
<P>
There was a lockout prior to the 1995-96 season that postponed
summer leagues and delayed free-agent signings, but no games were
missed. There was another lockout lasting just minutes in the
summer of 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
