<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water-Borne Diseases Spread in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Water-borne diseases such as
diarrhea and dysentery have spread in an epidemic form in
Bangladesh's flood-hit areas, already claiming more than 30 lives
and attacking 59,080 people, press reports said Friday quoting
health officials.
</P>
<P>
The government departments concerned have already sent about
4,000 medical teams with more than 2,000 doctors to the affected
areas to contain the situation. At the same time about 100
temporary medical centers have also opened across the flood-hit
districts to provide treatment to the victims.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladesh Red Crescent Society has already issued an
international appeal for 1.7 million U.S. dollars in aid for the
flood victims. It also requested the World Health Organization
(WHO) to send about 5 million water-purifying tablets to ensure
pure drinking water for the marooned people and keep them safe
from the diseases in the aftermath of the flood.
</P>
<P>
Since early the July-October monsoon season, this South Asian
country has been seriously hit by flood, which has already
affected 37 of its 64 districts, with more than 17.4 million
people becoming flood victims.
</P>
<P>
The death toll caused by flood has exceeded 270, officials of
the Ministry of Disaster management and Relief said.
</P>
<P>
Up till now, the flood has also washed away and damaged 420,000
hectares of cropland, 5,100 kilometers of roads and about 2,400
kilometers of embankment with more than 2,200 bridges and
culverts, according to the officials.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Disaster Management and Relief and other
government departments concerned have already distributed over
13.2 million taka (about 280,850 dollars), about 30,000 tons of
foodstuff and large quantities of other relief materials among the
flood-affected people.
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, the overall flood situation in the country was
improving further as water in the major rivers had started
receding, the Flood Forecasting and Warning Center (FFWC) said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
However, the monsoon remained fairly active over the country
and 10 rivers of Brahmaputra, Ganges and Meghna basins were still
flowing above danger marks at 13 places, the FFWC warned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
