<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin America over the past few days:
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguayan exports to Brazil amounted to 531
million U.S. dollars and imports were 423 million dollars during
the first six months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Sales and purchases with the neighboring country increased 15
percent and 9 percent respectively, compared with the same period
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chilean exports to Mercosur dropped by 5.28 percent
to 818 million dollars in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
Exports to Brazil dropped 9.39 percent to total 401 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Sales of motor vehicles in Brazil amounted to
106,000 units in July, a 23 percent decrease, the biggest drop
this year.
</P>
<P>
However, the National Association of Motor Vehicles
Manufacturers of Brazil plans to increase its sales of vehicle in
the country in coming months, thanks to the recent 5 percent
reduction in taxes on industrialized products.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chilean exports to the North American Free Trade
Agreement (Nafta) countries dropped by 1.7 percent in January-June
to 1.6 billion dollars, compared with the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank said Chilean exports to the United States were
down 8.72 percent to 1.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- Panama exported 1.6 million boxes of cantaloupes
to the United States, earning 13 million dollars so far this year.
</P>
<P>
Central America exports some 8 million boxes of cantaloupes to
the United States and European markets. The biggest exporters of
this fruit are Honduras, Guatemala, Costa Rica and Panama. 
</P>
</TEXT>
