<HEADLINE> Major Fujian Cities Report Continued Investment, Trade Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The major cities in the
southeastern region of east China's Fujian Province continued to
experience economic and trade expansion during the first half this
year despite the mounting effects of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Fuzhou, the provincial capital, approved 263 overseas-funded
projects in the first six months, with contracted overseas
investment climbing to 650 million U.S. dollars. These two figures
represent 19 and 53 percent gains, respectively, over the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
In the Xiamen Special Economic Zone, pledged and paid-in
overseas investment grew 116 percent and 6.6 percent year-on-year,
respectively, in the first half.
</P>
<P>
In the coastal city of Zhangzhou, ongoing overseas-funded
enterprises increased investment by 197 million U.S. dollars
during the same period.
</P>
<P>
Exports from these cities also grew an average of more than 10
percent in the first half, according to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
The southeastern section of Fujian is the most economically
advanced in the province and usually accounts for over 70 percent
of the province's total overseas investment and exports.  
</P>
