<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria to Change Currency Value Next July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, August 6 (Xinhua)-- The Bulgarian government announced
its first currency value reform in decades Thursday in a bid to
stablize the economy in order to facilitate ease of payments.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria will change its currency's face value by slashing
three digits beginning on July 1, 1999, officials said. A new
Bulgarian lev will be equal to 1,000 old ones, or one Deutsche
Mark.
</P>
<P>
The Bulgarian National Bank President Svetoslav Gavriski said
the transformation is a technical procedure and would not cause
losses to anyone, reported the Bulgarian Telegraph Agency (BTA).
</P>
<P>
BTA said, the old lev and the new one will be in use
simultaneously till December 31,1999. After that the old lev will
be withdrawn from circulation. But the old lev holders still can
exchange them for the new lev for a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
The currency re-valuation is the first since 1962. It is not
yet sure how many kinds of notes the new currency will have. The
old lev has several face values ranging from 100,000 lev to 100
lev.
</P>
<P>
In July last year, post-crisis Bulgaria established a currency
control board, according to deals with the International Monetary
Fund (IMF). The currency control board fixed the exchange rate of
the lev at 1,000 to one Deutsche Mark. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0250 </DOCNO>
