<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Majority of Bulgarians Have Pleasant Memories of Zhivkov </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- More than half of all Bulgarians
have favorable memories of Todor Zhivkov, their former head of
state, according to an opinion poll conducted by the Fact Agency
Thursday, one day after his death.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 88 percent of the 398 respondents interviewed in Sofia
and six other cities thought the name of Zhivkov would have a
memorable place in the country's history.
</P>
<P>
About 20 percent of the people thought that Zhivkov had done
many good things for Bulgaria, compared with one-third who alleged
that he had abused his power for his own benefit.
</P>
<P>
Forty-four percent described his term in office as successful
while 39 percent of the people held the opposite view.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-seven percent saw him as their "savior" and 16 percent
believed the situation would have been the same if Zhivkov had
remained in power. About 38 percent thought it would be worse.
</P>
<P>
Forty-four percent of those interviewed believed their
expectations of a better life were unobtainable after Zhivkov lost
power, while only eight percent found their dreams fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
Zhivkov was in power for 35 years from 1954 until 1989 when he
lost power and was expelled from the Bulgarian Communist Party. He
died Wednesday in a Sofia hospital at the age of 86. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungary to Provide Free Milk to School Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Hungary has found a solution to
its surplus dairy products: free milk for school children
throughout the nation.
</P>
<P>
The country has a high milk output and dairy farmers always
find it difficult to market their milk, while many children and
their families cannot afford to buy it.
</P>
<P>
To solve the problem, the Hungarian Agriculture and Rural
Development Ministry recently decided to offer a certain amount of
milk free to children around the nation.
</P>
<P>
Szabolcsszatmar State, which produces a large quantity of milk,
will be the first to introduce the new program. Each of the
85,000 children in all the state's nurseries, kindergartens and
elementary schools will receive 0.25 liters of milk everyday.
</P>
<P>
Children over the rest of the country will begin to receive the
milk beginning January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Agriculture and Rural Development Ministry and the national
dairy association will share the expense. 
</P>
</TEXT>
