<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shell Thailand Plans to Shed 150 Local Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The oil-marketing arm of Royal
Dutch/Shell in Thailand will take an unprecedented decision to
shed 150 of its 1,012 jobs to seek a leaner corporate structure,
it was learned here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The company confirmed a newspaper report that it will downsize
its stuff in Thailand by 15 percent as part of its worldwide
business reorganization.
</P>
<P>
Shell Co. of Thailand is the first major foreign oil firm to
embark on large-scale redundancies following major rationalization
within the local oil marketing industry.
</P>
<P>
The Bangkok Post Friday quoted John Withrington, chairman of
the Shell companies in Thailand, as saying the layoffs were not
part of a cost-cutting exercise.
</P>
<P>
He described them as a reorganization to improve the company's
efficiency to deal with the new environment characterized by
fierce competition, tight market margins, high operating costs and
slumping demand.
</P>
<P>
Withrington said the decision to shed staff had nothing to do
with the forthcoming new labor law which will force employers to
pay more in severance benefits to laid-off employees.
</P>
<P>
The company said it will help those taking part in an early
retirement scheme and senior employees of advanced age to manage
their finances.
</P>
<P>
Those made redundant will be given life insurance and health
insurance for a period of five years in addition to compensation
higher than the legal requirement while financial advisory
services will be provided on how to start up a business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0257 </DOCNO>
