<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy, Tunisia Sign Repatriation Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Italy and Tunisia signed an
agreement here on Thursday on the repatriation of illegal
immigrants, teh ANSA news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The agreement stressed that joint efforts to control illegal
immigration should contribute to "respect for human rights," which
underpin Italian commitments to help development in Tunisia's most
depressed zones.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Tunisia will gradually strengthen its
coastal controls to prevent the departure of illegal immigrants.
Other measures include provisions for identifying the illegals,
necessary before repatriation.
</P>
<P>
The agreement applies to all illegal immigrants intercepted
after departure from Tunisian territory, excepting nationals of
some other North African Arab states.
</P>
<P>
Italian foreign ministry officials said they value this clause
because it would further discourage immigrant traffickers who sail
nationals of some African countries as well as Asians to Italy
from Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini said the agreement is
"particularly satisfying and of great political significance." In
bringing a systematic approach for the two countries, it placed
their relationship in this field on "new and constructive
foundations."
</P>
<P>
The agreement with Tunisia is one among a series of
repatriation agreements that Italy has signed with countries from
which most of the illegal immigrants come. A similar agreement
was signed with Morocco on July 28. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
