<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Gold Market Recovers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Official statistics indicate
that gold sales in this economic and financial center of China
recovered in the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's gold sales totaled 3.4 tons in the first three
months of the year, up three percent from the same period last
year, and 17 percent from the last quarter of 1997, according to
figures released by the World Gold Association.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide, a total of 52.3 tons of gold was sold in the
Chinese mainland between January and March this year, with a total
value of 6.8 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Industry experts say they are optimistic about gold sales this
year. Tang Qing, general manager of a gold shop in Suzhou, which
neighbors Shanghai, said that people often turn to gold products
in times of economic recessions.
</P>
<P>
Li Yanming, manager of the China section of the World Gold
Association, said that the Chinese mainland has a huge market
potential for gold sales.
</P>
<P>
Though the varieties of ornaments keep increasing, gold jewelry
accounted for over 80 percent of all jewelry sales in Chinese
mainland market last year, and will likely continue to do so this
year, Li said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
