<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Lower House Passes Anti-Dumping Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Lower House Thursday
passed a bill to protect local industry from the dumping of
foreign products, the newspaper The Bangkok Post reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The bill, proposed by Supachai Panitchpakdi, deputy prime
minister and commerce minister, was passed with all-party support.
</P>
<P>
Pressure for anti-dumping control built up after Thailand
signed a World Trade Organization agreement to combat
protectionism to protect the country from unfair trading partners.
</P>
<P>
The bill provides for heavy import duties on foreign products
deemed to be on the local market at a lower cost than in the
countries of origin.
</P>
<P>
It also includes a clause to enable trading partners to appeal
if they can prove the products in question are not dumped to
damage local industry or monopolize the market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
