<HEADLINE> Tourism Environment in Tibet More Favorable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Whether it's staying at the Holiday
Inn, finding a well-trained guide, or getting on a bus to Mount
Qomolangma (Mt. Everest), tourists are now finding travel in the
Tibet Autonomous Region much more convenient.
</P>
<P>
As many as 42 travel agencies, including 21 international ones,
now have state approval in Tibet, the mysterious and attracting
land in southwest China, which now has 14 star hotels and more
than 50 tourism hotels. In the first half of this year, about 380
guides and attendants received training to work in the service
industry in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
On routes extending in all directions, several kinds of state
tourist transportation along much-improved roads are available
every day.
</P>
<P>
Regarding tourism as one of its five pillar industries, the
government of the Tibet Autonomous Regional has invested heavily in
building its tourism infrastructural facilities.
</P>
<P>
Besides completing the construction of the Lhasa International
Airport, the government has rebuilt the roads from Lhasa to many
scenic spots, and maintains such popular destinations as the
Potala Palace and Mount Qomolangma, the highest summit on earth.
</P>
<P>
The government has also developed five tourist centers with a
variety of unique vivid features, including Lhasa for the Tibetan
culture, Mount Qomolangma for mountain-climbing, the Yarlung
Zangbo River Gorge for ecological scientific investigations and
the Yalong River Valley, the birthplace of Tibetan ethnic group,
for its distinctive characteristics.  
</P>
</TEXT>
