<HEADLINE> China Works to Help the Deaf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese medical experts are
working hard to return the deaf to the world of sound, according
to the Sixth Asia-Pacific Congress on Deafness that closed on
Thursday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
More than 400 medical scientists, rehabilitation specialists
and special educators from 12 countries, including the United
States, Great Britain, Japan and Australia, exchanged views on the
treatment of deafness during the four-day meeting that ended on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
As a chronic condition afflicting the mankind for ages, hearing
impediments are one of the five major disabling conditions in
China, with approximately 24 million sufferers.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Han Demin, chairman of the congress's organizing
committee, said China's ability to prevent and treat deafness has
greatly improved in recent years, and that several ear-operation
techniques currently in use have reached or exceeded the
international standards.
</P>
<P>
In order to help improve the education of hearing-loss
sufferers in China, the Ministry of Health and Australia signed a
memorandum in 1993 calling for the two countries to jointly train
personnel engaged in educating the deaf. Training for the first
group of these specialists has now been completed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Why Philippine Stocks Dive to 5-Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine stocks dived to a
new five-year low Thursday after Wednesday's reprieve, reflecting
wide-spread pessimism about the direction of the country's
economy.
</P>
<P>
The main stock index tumbled 43.86 points, or 2.88 percent to
1,480.89 at the close on Thursday, the lowest since April 2, 1993,
when the index reached 1,475.97.
</P>
<P>
Share prices are now back to the 1993 level, erasing all gains
squirreled in half a decade.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's technical bounce was short-lived, with investors
taking it as an opportunity to flee as the market appeared headed
toward 1,400 points, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The market blood-bath, with prices of some issues below book
value, was caused by further deterioration in investor confidence
in the Philippine economy, they noted.
</P>
<P>
"Our market is in a lot of pain... The biggest factor is the
loss of confidence, the utter disgust for what is happening," said
Ramon Garcia, president of Diversified Securities Inc.
</P>
<P>
The market is worried that the economic growth in the first
half of the year may turn out weaker than expected, as did
corporate results. It was reported that the earnings of Ayala
Corp., the country's major corporation, were almost flat in the
first six months of the year, while those of another big company,
ALI, slumped 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Philippine Socio-Economic Planning Secretary
Felipe Medalla said the second-quarter economic growth is "not
going to be better than the first quarter. I'll be surprised if
the economy in the second quarter performed better than the
first."
</P>
<P>
"Hopefully, the second quarter will be the worst (period for
the economy), then (we expect) some recovery after that," Medalla
said.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of this year, gross national product (GNP)
of the Philippines grew by 2.5 percent and its gross domestic
product (GDP) 1.7 percent, the slowest in several years.
</P>
<P>
The economic growth may gradually pick up in the next two
quarters as interest rates and inflation ease and measures are
carried out to bridge the budget deficit, allowing the government
to achieve its target of 2-3 percent growth for GNP and 1.5-2.5
percent for GDP this year, economists said.
</P>
<P>
Government data released Wednesday show inflation in July
softening to 10.6 percent on the year from 10.7 percent in June
due to the stabilization of food prices.
</P>
<P>
Despite the release of the July inflation rate, the poor
economic performance in the first half of the year will push
investors to continuously sell Philippine shares, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a weak Japanese yen, fragile U.S. stocks and a sharp
dive on Hong Kong's share market also affect the mood in the
Philippine stock market.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese currency fell to nearly 145 yen to the U.S. dollar
in late Tokyo trade from around 144 yen Thursday, putting
pressures on an economic recovery in the Asian region.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine shares were also hurt by worries that U.S.
stocks could be in for another sharp fall, despite a mild recovery
overnight. The Dow plunged more than 3 percent Tuesday, sending
tremors through world markets.
</P>
<P>
As part of a regional phenomenon, the Philippine currency, the
peso, sagged to 42.7 against the greenback Thursday, the lowest in
four months. The peso's downturn also had a negative impact on the
stock market, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Analysts predicted that the Philippine stock market may further
go down to test the year's intra-day low of 1,450, but they see
bargain-hunters waiting in the sidelines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Deputy PM to Bid for WTO Position </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Deputy Prime Minister
and Commerce Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi has confirmed that he
would run as a candidate for the position of the World Trade
Organization (WTO) chief, the newspaper The Nation reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Supachai said Thursday that he would formally request Prime
Minister Chuan Leekpai to nominate him for the position.
</P>
<P>
If his request is approved by Chuan, the Thai Foreign Ministry
would be responsible for submitting his name to the WTO.
</P>
<P>
Earlier last week, Chuan said he was reluctant to let go of his
deputy as he felt Supachai could contribute to the country's
economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that if Supachai were to leave, it would adversely
affect the ruling Democrat Party and the government as his
economic expertise would be difficult to replace.
</P>
<P>
But the prime minister also said the decision was Supachai's
and he would not veto his bid to become head of the world trade
body.
</P>
<P>
Supachai said he would retire from politics if he was elected
to the WTO job.
</P>
<P>
He insisted that he made the decision on personal aspirations
and was not trying to escape from rumored conflicts with Finance
Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda.
</P>
<P>
He also said his decision was moderately risky as the
application does not ensure that he will get the job.
</P>
<P>
Candidates for the position must be nominated by their
governments before September 30. The term of the current WTO
director-general, Renato Ruggiero of Italy, expires next April 30.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
