<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Computer Accessories Imports Up Notablely in Chinese Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Beijing's imports of computer
parts and accessories have risen more than a quarter in the first
half year over last year, feeding the capital's increasingly
hungry information technology industry, today's China Daily
reported.
</P>
<P>
Beijing Customs said that 38.24 million U.S. dollars of spare
parts and accessories were imported in the first half of this year,
representing a year-to-year increase of 27.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Imports via bonded warehouseds, which allow importers to
temporarily store goods in China without paying import tariffs,
have risen in recent years because of their low risk and high
flexibility.
</P>
<P>
Statistics indicate that imports via bonded warehouses were 54
percent of the total spare parts imported in the first half of the
year, up from 38.1 percent in 1996 and 25.2 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Imports from the U.S. amounted to 20.35 million U.S. dollars,
more than half the total. Other major sellers include Malaysia,
Japan, the Republic of Korea and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the robust rise of imports partly results
from lower prices because of Asian financial turmoil and
widespread currency devaluation.
</P>
<P>
But, there is also a growing appetite for computers. Demand
grows here at a rate triple the world average.
</P>
<P>
Some key computer components, such as microprocessing chips,
central processing units and hard disks, depend largely on
imports, though China's computer industry is growing quickly.
</P>
<P>
Also, some large Chinese home appliance giants, such as
Changhong, Haier and Hisense, are marching to break into the
information industry. They may have money and resources for China
to vitalize the industry by producing more China-made computer
parts, experts said.
</P>
<P>
Around 10 million computers will be sold in Beijing by the year
2000, making itself one of the three largest computer markets in
the world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Structural Readjustment In Northeast China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Liaoning Province, a leading
heavy industrial center in northeast China, is using structural
readjustment to offset the effects of the Asian financial crisis
and to meet its economic goal this year.
</P>
<P>
Investment from Asian countries this year is down 32.6 percent,
with Japan's the biggest drop, at 54.9 percent. Over half the
overseas investment in this province in the past few years has
come from Japan, the Republic of Korea (ROK), and Tailand.
</P>
<P>
Exports to ROK were also down 31 percent, and those to
Southeast Asia, by 38 percent. Under these circumstance, the
province has turned its emphasis of developing other areas.
</P>
<P>
As a result, exports to the United States increased 22 percent
and to European countries, 52 percent, according to Wen Shizhen,
secretary of the provincial Communist Party Committee.
</P>
<P>
Wen says the province will continue to readjust its economic
structure and export product mix and develop hi-tech products in
the latter half of the year.
</P>
<P>
It will also encourage companies with better performance to
build plants in Africa and the Middle East, to increase their
market share abroad, and to form joint ventures with foreign
companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
