<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Village Election Held In Spite Of Heavy Rain (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, August 8 (Xinhua)-- Early one recent morning in the
summer breeze, the villagers of Hadahso in north China's Inner
Mongolia Autonomous Region woke with excitement to go out, not to
work in the fields, but to vote for a new village committee.
</P>
<P>
The central voting area was in a square in front of the
committee office building, which had been carefully decorated with
a banner reading: "Third Village Committee Election".
</P>
<P>
There were five red ballot boxes and desks with wooden
partitions. A 10-meter by 2-meter area around each box was marked
by rope. On the sides of the square there were two blackboards for
election results.
</P>
<P>
At about 5 o'clock, more than 700 villagers had gathered and
were chatting cheerfully, but then it began to drizzle. Some women
with children ran into the building. One villager named Liu Huan
hurried into the third election section and took off his shirt to
shelter the ballot box. Soon, umbrellas were opened above the five
boxes.
</P>
<P>
As it continued to rain quietly, people were talking heatedly
under the umbrellas: "Is Liu Yuguo, who is lame, competent to be
head of the village committee? " to which someone else replied,
"But he's educated, upright, and not corrupt."
</P>
<P>
Another person chimed in; "That's right. I'll vote for him, as
long as we can become rich under his leadership."
</P>
<P>
The election started at 6 o'clock and it began to rain more
heavily, making a drumming noise on the umbrellas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
