<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forest Fires Still Roaring Around Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Forest fires fanned by strong winds
blazed away in Italy today as thick smoke blanketed major roads
and caused at least one serious accident.
</P>
<P>
The northwestern region of Liguria was effectively cut in half
by a blaze on the coastal riviera near Genoa. Black smoke
billowed onto the A-12 motorway and forced its closure to traffic
for most of the day.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of tourists were evacuated as a blaze swept through a
campsite at Deiva Marina, burning tents, campers and holiday
bungalows.
</P>
<P>
At Eboli near Salerno, 11 people were hurt as smoke caused a
pile-up on a state highway. The most serious injury was to a
9-year-old child who is reported to be in a coma.
</P>
<P>
Firefighters said the situation was also "critical" in
Calabria, Tuscany and other parts of Campania, the region around
Naples.
</P>
<P>
But fire-fighters managed to put out a blaze at Maratea, in the
Basilicata region, just before it reached a hotel and a group of
houses on the outskirts of the coastal town.
</P>
<P>
To cope with the fire emergency, Interior Minister Giorgio
Napolitano today signed a decree earmarking 20 billion lire (11
million dollars) for the regions of Calabria, Sicily and Sardinia.
</P>
<P>
Outside Italy, flames continued to claim victims today as a man
was burned to death on a Greek mountain as he tried to save his
house, while two others died on a Croatian island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
