<HEADLINE> Highlights of Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The Communist Party of China (CPC) Central Committee, State
Council, and Central Military Commission, sent telegrams of
appreciation today to millions of Chinese soldiers and civilians
participating in the flood control effort.
</P>
<P>
Central authorities praised the leading and crucial role the
CPC committees and governments at all levels have played in
organizing military and civilians to participate in the massive
effort to battle the heaviest flooding since 1954.
</P>
<P>
-- Floods have killed more than 2,000 people since mid-June
and affected 240 million -- a quarter of China's population -- in
28 provinces, municipalities and autonmous regions, a senior
official with the Ministry of Civil Affairs said yesterday at a
news conference in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The floods, worst since 1954, have destroyed 5.58 million
houses, damaged another 12.05 million and forced the evacuation of
13.8 million people.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph
</P>
<P>
-- Li Peng, China's top legislator, recently stressed the
importance of pollution control and environmental protection and
the implementation of related laws and regulations.
</P>
<P>
Li, chairman of the National People's Congress (NPC) Standing
Committee, made the comments in a fact-finding trip to Dalian in
northeast China's Liaoning Province between August 4 to 6.
</P>
<P>
-- The state-owned and collectively-run enterprises dismissed
more than 4 million workers in the first half of this year,
according to the latest statistics of the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also indicated that 1.48 million of the laid-offs
have transfered to non-government and privately-run ventures.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The water level of the Yangtze River yesterday surpassed the
record height recorded in 1954, when a catastrophic flood had to
be diverted three times, and could rise still further today --
with a new flood crest expected.
</P>
<P>
The news came amid indications that Hubei Province, which
yesterday declared a state of emergency, is coming under growing
pressure to divert flash flooding in the Jingjiang section of the
Yangtze River, which will require the approval of the State
Council.
</P>
<P>
-- Police have arrested two suspects alleged to have been
involved in the illegal detention and subsequent death of Taiwan
Lin Ti-chuan, Deputy Director of the Anshan Public Security
Bureau Liu Linlin announced yesterday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
