<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Female Population Sees Faster Increase in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Yangon, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar's female population is
estimated to have reached 23.36 million in the 1997-98 fiscal year
which ended in March, 320,000 more than the number of males,
according to the latest official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Of the total 46.4 million population at the end of the fiscal
year, which maintained an annual growth rate of 1.84 percent,
females accounted for 50.34 percent and males 49.66 percent.
</P>
<P>
The country's female population increased by 420,000 in the
year over the previous fiscal year while the male population rose
by 410,000 only.
</P>
<P>
The statistics show that 7.58 million or 32.45 percent of the
female population is in the age group under 15, 13.85 million or
59.29 percent in the working-age group of 15-59 and 1.93 million
or 8.26 percent in the age group of 60 and above.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar women have had a long history of access to education.
In the basic education system, the proportion of female to male
students is one to one according to a study on the education
sector while female students in higher education comprise about 58
percent of the total enrollment.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the national literacy rate of women has gone up to
71.3 percent in the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Under the leadership of the Myanmar National Committee for
Women's Affairs formed after the 1995 Beijing Declaration adopted
at the Fourth World Conference on Women, the country is
implementing a national action plan to speed up efforts for
improving women's conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiangsu Tourism Sees Steady Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The tourism industry of east
China's Jiangsu Province grew steadily in the first half of this
year, with numbers for both domestic and overseas tourists rising
slightly over last year.
</P>
<P>
Some 28.36 million Chinese residents toured Jiangsu in the
first six months, up 10 percent from a year ago, while the number
of overseas travelers inched up by 2.3 percent to more than
469,800 in the period.
</P>
<P>
As the Chinese currency, the Renminbi yuan, continued to remain
stable, some 9,965 residents took trips overseas during the first
half, a surge of 45.5 percent over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
An analysis indicates that the additional overseas tourists
came mainly from Canada, France, Australia, Italy, the
Netherlands, Singapore, Thailand, Japan, the United States, and
Spain.
</P>
<P>
The overseas destinations of tourists from Jiangsu included
Singapore, Malaysia, Thailand, the Philippines, Hong Kong, Macao
and some countries in western Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dalian's Half-Year Exports up 20 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Exports of this port city of
northeast China's Liaoning Province continued to grow despite the
mounting negative effects of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Dalian's exports in the first half of this year were more than
20 percent higher than last year, according to official
statistics.
</P>
<P>
Official figures also show that Dalian reaped 1.61 billion
U.S. dollars in export earnings in the first six months of this
year.
</P>
<P>
An analysis indicates that the export earnings of
overseas-funded enterprises in Dalian reached 1.06 billion U.S.
dollars for the January-June period, an increase of 23.3 percent
from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Dalian's 79 production enterprises that conduct foreign trade
on their own had a combined 274 million U.S. dollars in export
earnings in the first six months, a jump of more than 70 percent
year-on-year.
</P>
<P>
Exports of electronics and machinery totaled 850 million U.S.
dollars, more than half of Dalian's total exports for the
January-June period.
</P>
<P>
Due to the effects of the Asian financial crisis, Dalian's
exports to Hong Kong, Southeast Asia and the Republic of Korea
declined in the first six months compared with a year ago.
</P>
<P>
However, Dalian's exports to Europe more than doubled while
those to North American nations increased by 60 percent on a
yearly basis in the first five months. Both figures are all-time
highs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Children Get Free Corrective Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- With the help of Operation Smile
1998, Lei Zhifu, a one-year-old baby girl born with a harelip, may
soon have a perfect smile, said today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Operation Smile, a US-based non-profit organization that
provides poor children free corrective surgery, brought 51 doctors
from the United States, Hong Kong, Columbia, Philippines and
Singapore to work alongside Chinese doctors at Beijing's Plastic
Surgery Hospital to operate on 200 children with harelips or cleft
palates.
</P>
<P>
Doctors will perform free surgeries over the next few days.
</P>
<P>
They are sponsored by Operation Smile International, the China
Women and Children Development Center and the Plastic Surgery
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time Operation Smile has come to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 2,000 children have received corrective surgeries since
Operation Smile first came to China in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Harelips and cleft palates are the most common form of
congenital deformity, affecting one out of every 550 babies born
in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
