<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Monica Lewinsky Testifies before Grand Jury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky Thursday testified before a grand jury in a
courtroom here about her relationship with U.S. President Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Her spokeswoman said she testified "truthfully, completely and
honestly."
</P>
<P>
"Monica and her family are relieved that this ordeal finally
appears to be coming to an end," family spokeswoman Judy Smith
said at a news conference shortly after Lewinsky ended a long day
of testimony.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is scheduled to answer questions before the same grand
jury on August 17.
</P>
<P>
Lewinsky was to testify she had a sexual relationship with the
president and discussed ways of concealing it but was never
instructed to lie under oath, news reports quoted legal sources as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The account would reverse her own sworn affidavit, directly
conflict with the president's sworn testimony in January that he
did not engage in sexual activity with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
"She answered each question truthfully, completely and honestly
that was posed to her by the Office of Independent Counsel and
also questions that were posed to her by members of the grand
jury," Smith said.
</P>
<P>
Smith declined to say whether Lewinsky would have to return to
the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
Lewinsky's appearance completed a deal struck last week that
removed her and her parents from any legal jeopardy with a grant
of immunity from prosecution.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile Clinton went about his business at the White House,
hosting an anti-crime event in the Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
"His mood is great," White House deputy press secretary Barry
Toiv said.
</P>
<P>
"We're hopeful that this means a four-year investigation that
has cost upward of 40 million dollar is finally coming to a
conclusion," Toiv said, referring to Independent Counsel Kenneth
Starr's investigation that started with the Whitewater land deal
in Arkansas and expanded to questions of obstruction of justice
inside the White House.
</P>
<P>
On Capitol Hill, House Democratic Leader Richard Gephardt,
referring to the Lewinsky investigation at a news conference,
said, "I'm sick of hearing about it."
</P>
<P>
He said it would be a "grave mistake" for Starr to send a
report to Congress on the investigation in the weeks leading up to
the fall elections.
</P>
<P>
"That would be very partisan, very unfair and demeaning to the
process that I think all of us believe is important to this
country," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungary Demands Yugoslav Ethnic Hungarians off Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, August 6 (Xinhua)-- Hungary urged Yugoslavia on
Thursday to immediately stop sending Yugoslav ethnic Hungarian
soldiers and policemen to Kosovo, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The Hungarian Foreign Ministry's Political State Secretary
Nemet Zsolt made the appeal to the Yugoslav ambassador in
Budapest, the Hungarian Telegraph Agency (HTA) reported.
</P>
<P>
HTA said, Zsolt told the ambassador that Hungary was deeply
concerned about the escalation of the Kosovo crisis and
Yugoslavia's practice of sending ethnic Hungarians to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Since early August, Yugoslavia has been recruiting ethnic
Hungarian volunteers and reserves in Vojvodina and sending ethnic
Hungarian police officers to Kosovo, a Yugoslav province where
ethnic Albanians are seeking independence from Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Zsolt said the situation has forced Hungary to reiterate its
stance and demand that authorities in Belgrade stop such actions
at once.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Zsolt said Hungary is willing to continue
developing bilateral relations with Yugoslavia and a halt to
sending ethnic Hungarians to Kosovo would be conducive to the
development of the relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
