<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cotton Prices Rise in U.S. Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Cotton futures prices were
rising in the past two days on both the New York Cotton Exchange
and the Chicago Board of Trade, said reports reaching here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Cotton for December delivery Thursday rose 1.7 cents to 72.88
cents a pound on the New York Cotton Exchange.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, December cotton rose 1.01 cents to 71.18 cents a
pound on the Chicago Board of Trade.
</P>
<P>
Market participants pointed out two major factors behind the
increase of cotton futures prices.
</P>
<P>
One is the lower production estimates in the United
States. Sparks Co. of Memphis predicted a cotton crop of 14.196
million bales in the United States after drought wiped out parts
of the crop in Texas and other southern states. The new estimates
are well below the prediction of 15 million bales by the
U.S. Agricultural Department earlier.
</P>
<P>
The other is the worst flood China is suffering in more than 40
years. Market sources say the flooding has wiped out some crops in
Chinese cotton-growing regions, which could cause China to reduce
exports and possibly import more cotton later this year.
</P>
<P>
China and the United States are the world's two biggest
cotton-growing countries. Market analysts believe that both
countries contend yearly for the title of the world's largest
producer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
