<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Gives Less Fertilizers to Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar distributed less chemical
fertilizers to its farmers in the 1997-98 fiscal year which ended
in March despite the fact that it procured a large amount of them
locally and from abroad.
</P>
<P>
Of the 394,000 tons of fertilizers obtained by the state-run
Myanmar Agriculture Services (MAS) and other organizations,
289,000 tons were distributed, a decrease of 35,000 tons over the
previous year, according to the latest official report on
agriculture in the fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the decrease to the inability of farmers
to operate on small holding because of rising prices.
</P>
<P>
The MAS distributed 117,000 tons of fertilizers, 63.9 percent
of the total amount sold to farmers.
</P>
<P>
Efforts are also being made for systematic utilization of
natural fertilizers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Myanmar is reportedly introducing effective
micro-organism fertilizers for boosting the yield of crops and
improved quality without affecting the environment.
</P>
<P>
Paddy, beans and pulses, cotton and sugarcane are designated as
major crops of Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Myanmar imported 59.5 million
U.S. dollars worth of fertilizers in the 1997-98 fiscal year, 47.5
million dollars more than the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The statistics also show that Myanmar's agriculture, the
mainstay of its economy traditionally accounting for 35 to 40
percent of the gross domestic product and 35 percent of the
export, grew by 2.9 percent in its output value in the fiscal
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
