<HEADLINE> Flood Watcher Working Long Hours on Dongting Lake Dam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Lin Hongwu has been working long
hours for more than a week at the Qilishan Hydrologic Station of
Chenglingji, the confluence of the Yangtze River and Dongting Lake.
</P>
<P>
Because of persistent rainfall along the upper reaches of the
Yangtze River, the water level of the lake has lingered at about
35 meters, surpassing the warning level for almost a month.
</P>
<P>
Every day Lin works for 12 hours, checking the water level
every 30 minutes, much more frequently than the normal four times
a day.
</P>
<P>
Although an automatic meter is used to record the rise and fall
of water, Lin never gives up checking the records at the water's
edge.
</P>
<P>
"We must guarantee the accuracy and timeliness of the flood
report," he said. "Every time the water level climbs to a new high
point, I am feeling quite heavy at heart for the floods are
threatening people."
</P>
<P>
Lin's father used to be a hydrologist working at Qilishan
Station. Both Lin and his elder brother followed in their father's
footsteps. Lin, 29, has already been working at the station for 12
years.
</P>
<P>
His brother is working at Anxiang Hydrologic Station 100 km
away, an area inundated by floods several days ago. They moved
water surveying meters to a boat and continued to work.
</P>
<P>
Since the British set up the first customs water gauge at
Chenglingji in 1904, the hydrologic station here has recorded the
rise and fall of the water at Dongting Lake.
</P>
<P>
Affected by serious soil erosion on the upper reaches of the
Yangtze River, the water surface area is decreasing but floods
occur almost every year.
</P>
<P>
At noon on last Sunday, Lin's father made phoned to ask him to
come home for lunch. The offer was rejected by Lin, who said that
he was only able to leave the station for a few minutes.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that my father can understand; it was he who
introduced me and my brother to the hydrologic station," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicaragua Commission to Solve Border Row with Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Nicaragua will set up a
commission to resolve the dispute over the San Juan River between
Nicaragua and Costa Rica, Nicaraguan Vice President Enrique
Nicolas Bolanos said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Bolanos said the commission will draft regulations for
navigation on the San Juan border river.
</P>
<P>
He said the draft regulations will be discussed by the
authorities of Nicaragua and Costa Rica, with the aim of ending
the dispute over rights of navigation on the San Juan river
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Under conditions included in the regulations, Costa Rica must
request permission from Nicaragua when it needs to navigate on the
San Juan River with weapons, Bolanos said.
</P>
<P>
All officers who travel on the river must have passports,
declare the amount of weapons they are carrying, the time they
will enter or leave the river and the route.
</P>
<P>
Nicaragua will demand payment from Costa Rica when Nicaraguan
escorts accompany Costa Rican officers navigating on the river
with arms.
</P>
<P>
Under relevant treaties, the 300-kilometer section of the river
separating Costa Rica from Nicaragua is under Nicaragua's
sovereignty. Costa Rica has the right of free navigation through
this waterway.
</P>
<P>
However, the treaties have not specified whether the navigation
right covers armed Costa Rican officers patroling the river.
</P>
<P>
The latest dispute between the two nations flared up almost a
month ago when Nicaraguan authorities prohibited members of the
Costa Rica forces moving on the river with weapons.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Nicaragua suspended free navigation following a
heavy deployment of military personnel by Costa Rica. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
