<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ningxia Says Goodbye To Endemic, Infectious Diseases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Ningxia Hui
Autonomous Region has brought endemic and infectious diseases
under control thanks to efforts made since the region was
established four decades ago.
</P>
<P>
The region has said goodbye to four major endemic diseases,
namely the plague, iodine deficiency, fluorine poisoning and
brucellosis, and to 17 types of infectious diseases such as
measles, dysentery, diphtheria and epidemic encephalitis, all of
which had threatened local people for years.
</P>
<P>
Iodine deficiency, the number one endemic disease in the
region, is now under control in 77 townships in its 17 counties
and cities.
</P>
<P>
A total of 480,000 out of the 640,000 people threatened by
fluorine poisoning now use low-fluorine water for drinking and
cooking.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the efforts of concerned departments in the region,
the plague, which used to occur every five years, disappeared 33
years ago.
</P>
<P>
Ningxia has also speeded up the implementation of planned
immunization, and over 90 percent of its townships have now
adopted the immunization system.
</P>
<P>
The great efforts made to control endemic and infectious
diseases have helped reduce the incidence of acute infectious
diseases to a current rate of 323 per 100,000 people, down from
the 1958 ratio of 2,162 per 100,000 people, and the death rate
attributed to infectious diseases has dropped to 25 per 10 million
from 6,055 per 10 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
