<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Weather Changes in Past Two Decades </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- People who still remember
better summers or harder winters in New Zealand should not imagine
things like that, because there has been a big shift in New
Zealand climate during the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
According to a latest study of climate records and weather
features in New Zealand and the South Pacific by New Zealand
National Institute for Water and Atmospheric Research, a lot of
changes in New Zealand weather have taken place since 1977.
</P>
<P>
These changes include:
</P>
<P>
1. The north and east of New Zealand's North Island have become
 10 percent drier and 5 percent sunnier, with more droughts;
</P>
<P>
2. The west and south of New Zealand's South Island have become
10 percent wetter and 5 percent cloudier, with more damaging
floods;
</P>
<P>
3. There are fewer frosts nationally;
</P>
<P>
4. The retreat of the west coast glaciers has stopped, but
eastern glaciers continue to shrink; and
</P>
<P>
5. Night temperatures in New Zealand continue to rise.
</P>
<P>
The Dominion, a local newspaper, Friday quoted Paul Hargreaves,
chief executive of the institute, as saying the changes were
linked to larger-scale climate changes in the South Pacific and to
other worldwide variations.
</P>
<P>
Since 1977, he said, there has been more than 150 kilometers'
movement east of a vast belt of storms and winds in the South
Pacific convergence zone. El Nino events have become more
frequent, but they could not yet be linked with global warming.
</P>
<P>
Among impacts of the changes outlined by a number of
institutes, are poorer summer and autumn pasture growth in drier
areas, increased damage to soil in wetter areas, as well as
increasing fungal diseases, heat-induced Toxins, pests and
disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
