<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Doctors: Tour de France Drug Should not Be Banned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 7 (Xinhua) - Dutch doctors said on Friday that a
drug that taken by some riders during the Tour de France cycling
race should be excluded from the banned substances list.
</P>
<P>
Epoetin, the synthetic form of a natural substance called erythr
opoietin, controls the production of red blood cells in the body
that carry oxygen to tissues. It is banned by the International
Olympic Committee and the Union Cycliste Internationale.
</P>
<P>
Athletes'muscles need a lot of oxygen to perform well.Injecting
epoetin is one way of increasing performance,particularly in an
endurance competition.
</P>
<P>
France's 21-day cycling race was dubbed the "Tour de Farce"(The
Joke Tour) when six cycling teams quit the competition after
French police conducted a series of raids in search of banned
substances, including epoetin. Doctors, team officials and
cyclists are awaiting further questioning in connection with the
raids.
</P>
<P>
Professor Joammes Marx and Peter Vergouwen, of University
Hospital in Utrecht, argue that epoetin should not be considered a
doping drug.
</P>
<P>
"It is a very good and safe medicine, but now the point
is:should it be used by athletes?" local reports quoted Marx as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"Athletes, in principle, should not use drugs but this one,I
think, should be discussed by the International Olympic Committee
again. I'm not sure it should be a forbidden drug."
</P>
<P>
In a study published in The Lancet medicine journal, the
doctors showed that competitors who take the drug cannot be
reliably detected and that some athletes who have never used the
drug have packed-cell volume of 0.5, the limit of normality.
</P>
<P>
The drug cannot be detected in the body. In general,doctors
measure packed-cell volume, a measure of red-blood-cell
concentrations. The Union Cycliste Internationale set a cut-off of
0.5. Above that level epoetin is assumed to be used and the
cyclist is banned.
</P>
<P>
Marx and Vergouwen analysed blood samples of 18 men and 28
women athletes and 134 men and 144 women in a control group over
16 months. Four men athletes and four controls exceeded the limit.
</P>
<P>
"All six would have been excluded from competition according to
Union Cycliste Internationale rules despite their packed-cell
volumes being part of normally distributed values," Marx said in
the study.
</P>
<P>
As further proof he cited an Australian study of top cyclists
who were monitored over 10 years. Nearly three percent had
packed-cell volumes higher than 0.5.
</P>
<P>
Marx said athletes use iron, vitamins and food supplements to
enhance performance. He said some might be tempted to correct a
lower packed-cell volume by using a non-detectable substance such
as epoetin, as long as the value remains below 0.5.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged that everything possible should be done to
protect athletes against doping but added: "In the case of epo
etin, the International Olympic Commitee and Union Cycliste
Internationale might consider whether taking a non-detectable
substance that is able to correct a physiological inequality among
competitors should be considered doping."
</P>
<P>
Marx said epoetin, which is available through prescription,is
one of the best drugs ever developed. He said it has changed the
lives of patients on kidney dialysis and has improved the health
of anaemia patients. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   IAAF Withhold Two Athletes' Prize Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- World athletics governing body the
IAAF has decided to withhold the prize money for Kenyan
steeplechaser Paul Kosgei and an unnamed Romanian woman athlete
from two world championship events.
</P>
<P>
Since athletics went professional in 1985, it is the first time
the IAAF imposed financial sanctions, rather than suspensions,in
such a case.
</P>
<P>
The decision was taken at an International Amateur Athletic
Federation (IAAF) meeting in Seville, Spain, last June. Details
were given in a statement last weekend but the IAAF refused to
identify the athletes.
</P>
<P>
However, Kosgei's new manager, Italian agent Gianni DeMadonna,
confirmed on Thursday that the Kenyan had been sanctioned,
according to local reports.
</P>
<P>
Kosgei was bronze medallist in the 4-km world cross country
race at Marrakech last March.
</P>
<P>
IAAF secretary Istvan Gyulai said in a statement: "The prize
money of two athletes, due to them after the world cross country
championships in Marrakech and the world road relay championship
in Manaus, Brazil, will not be paid.
</P>
<P>
"The two athletes had undergone only one out-of-competition
test instead of the two required during the 12 months prior to the
competitions, a condition to be eligible to win competition
awards."
</P>
<P>
The total amount of cash withheld amounted to more than 40,000
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The IAAF stressed the punishment was not because of any
suggestion of a failed drug test or any refusal to test.
</P>
<P>
Gyulai added: "The two athletes could not be tested because the
IAAF did not know where they were." 
</P>
</TEXT>
