<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> War Factions in Afghanistan Urged to Reach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council of
the United Nations Thursday called on all war factions in
Afghanistan to stop all actions leading to the escalation of the
military confrontation and reach a cease-fire through
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
In a presidential statement, the Security Council expressed its
grave concern over the new sharp escalation of the military
confrontation by saying it is a growing threat to regional and
international peace and security, and demanded an urgent and
unconditional cease-fire leading to a final end to the
hostilities.
</P>
<P>
The council reiterated that the Afghan crisis can be settled
only by peaceful means, through direct negotiations between the
Afghan factions under United Nations auspices, aimed at achieving
mutually acceptable solutions accommodating the rights and
interests of all ethnic, religious and political groups of the
country.
</P>
<P>
The council called upon all Afghan parties to return to the
negotiating table without delay and preconditions and to cooperate
with the aim of creating a broad-based and fully representative
government, which would protect the rights of all Afghans and
observe the international obligations of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The council called on all states neighboring Afghanistan and
other states with influence in Afghanistan to intensify their
efforts under the aegis of the United Nations to bring the parties
to a negotiated settlement.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council urged all sates to refrain from any
outside interference in the internal affairs of Afghanistan,
including the involvement of foreign military personnel.
</P>
<P>
It reiterated that any such interference from abroad should
cease immediately and called on all states to end the supply of
arms and ammunition to all parties to the conflict and to take
resolute measures to prohibit their military personnel from
planning and participating in combat operation in the country.
</P>
<P>
The council once again called on all Afghan factions to
cooperate fully with the United Nations Special Mission to
Afghanistan and international humanitarian organizations and urged
them, in particular the Taliban, to take necessary steps to assure
the safety and freedom of movement of such personnel.
</P>
<P>
The council expressed its deep concern over the continuing
discrimination against girls and women and other violations of
human rights as well as violations of international humanitarian
law in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
