<HEADLINE> Clinton: U.S. to Keep Sanctions against Iraq in Place </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton said on
Thursday that Iraq's refusal to cooperate with U.N. weapons
inspectors was "unacceptable" and that it would strengthen U.S.
resolve to keep sanctions in place.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq's latest refusal to cooperate with the international
weapons inspectors is unacceptable," Clinton said in a statement
issued by the White House.
</P>
<P>
"Unless Iraq reverses course and cooperates fully with
international weapons inspectors, the United States will stop any
and all efforts to alter the sanctions regime," the president
said.
</P>
<P>
"Far from hastening the day the international community lifts
sanctions against Iraq, as Iraq intends, its failure to live up to
its obligations will perpetuate those sanctions and keep the Iraqi
economy under tight international control," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's statement came following a meeting of the U.N.
Security Council in New York, which also declared iraq's freeze of
cooperation with U.N. weapons inspectors "totally unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the U.S. State Department said Washington would oppose
any easing of sanctions against Iraq until Baghdad complies with
U.N. resolutions on weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
"We will oppose any change in the sanctions regime until Iraq
complies," spokesman James Foley told reporters.
</P>
<P>
But Foley said the United States did not consider the latest
dispute to be a crisis.
</P>
<P>
The latest dispute came as talks between chief U.N. weapons
inspector Richard Butler and Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq
Aziz broke down earlier this week becauser of Butlter's refusal to
declare that all Iraq's weapons of mass destruction had been
accounted for.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the White House said Iraq's decision to freeze
weapons inspections was unacceptable and vowed to keep pressure on
Iraq unless it complies with the U.N. resolution.
</P>
<P>
"This noncompliance is completely unacceptable," White House
spokesman P.J. Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
"We will not allow Iraq access to the resources necessary to
restart their weapons of mass destruction program," he said. "We
will keep the pressure on until Iraq complies fully" with the
U.N.-mandated inspections program.
</P>
<P>
Crowley also said Iraq failed to provide required escorts on
Thursday to a U.N. inspections team seeking to leave its compound
in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He said the failure to provide the escorts was an indication
that Iraq's threats of noncompliance were being carried out
although there had been no inspection scheduled.
</P>
<P>
"We have evidence on the ground that Iraq is beginning to
follow through on its threats," Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
He said Bill Richardson, U.S. ambassador to the United
Nations, had broken off a vacation to attend a U.N. Security
Council briefing by chief weapons inspector Richard Butler on
Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
