<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. House of Representatives Passes Campaign Finance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House of
Representatives on Thursday voted to ban large, unregulated
contributions to political parties that caused problems during the
1996 elections.
</P>
<P>
The measure, which passed 252-179 and could deny the parties a
multimillion-dollar source of campaign cash, faces long odds in
the Senate, where the campaign finance overhaul is opposed by
Republican leaders.
</P>
<P>
The Senate abandoned changing the campaign finance laws this
year after supporters couldn't break a Republican-led filibuster
and force a vote on a similar bill. Majority Leader Trent Lott has
no desire to resurrect the matter in the Senate's closing days of
the 105th Congress.
</P>
<P>
Backers of the measure, co-sponsored by Representatives
Christopher Shays, a Republican, and Marty Meehan, a Democrat,
hoped the strong House showing would spur the Senate. Sixty-one
Republicans, 190 Democrats and an independent voted for the bill,
while 164 Republicans and 15 Democrats were against it.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton, who favors the bill, called the vote a
"heartening sign for the health of our democracy" and urged the
Senate also to pass it.
</P>
<P>
Among other things, the Shays bill would ban use by national or
state parties of "soft money," unlimited and unregulated donations
from corporations, labor unions and individuals. It also would
regulate issue advertising, which purports to educate voters but
increasingly is used to influence elections. It also would expand
disclosure requirements.
</P>
<P>
Between January 1997 and June 1998, the two major parties
raised 115.8 million dollars in soft-money donations, according to
a study of campaign donations by Common Cause, an advocacy group
that supports changing the system of funding political campaigns.
The figure was more than double the 50 million dollars collected
in the corresponding period of the 1994 election cycle, the study
said.
</P>
<P>
House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, a Republican, said the bill
would damage the process.
</P>
<P>
"The effect of all this federal regulation is to chill free
speech and political participation," said DeLay, who led
Republican opposition to the reform effort.
</P>
<P>
The Shays-Meehan bill advanced to a final vote after surviving
an unusual procedure crafted by House Republican leaders that
stretched debate over many weeks and required votes on 11
different bills and dozens of amendments. The bill with the most
support advanced to final passage.
</P>
<P>
An alternative, known as the "freshman bill" and offered by a
bipartisan group of first-termers, represented the strongest
challenge to Shays. But the House rejected it Thursday by a
221-147 vote, with 61 members taking a neutral position by voting
"present."
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the House voted 237-186 in favor of Shays-Meehan.
</P>
<P>
Republicans generally raise and spend more money than Democrats
and have struggled to preserve the advantage. As they investigated
alleged fund-raising improprieties by Democrats during the 1996
election, they said it also made little sense to pass new campaign
finance laws when existing ones were being broken. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0319 </DOCNO>
