<HEADLINE> Russia Concerned about Iraq's New Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Russia is seriously concerned
about the new deterioration of relations between Iraq and the
Special Commission in charge of Iraq's disarmament, the Interfax
news agency reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Foreign Ministry said that Baghdad must comply with
U.N. Security Council resolutions and continue constructive
cooperation with U.N. Special Commission in charge of Iraq's
disarmament, and not make ultimatums.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi leadership Wednesday decided to suspend cooperation
with the commission and the International Atomic Energy Agency
(IAEA), accusing the commission of delaying intentionally the
implementation of its mandate on Iraq's disarmament.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Iraq criticized the U.N. Security Council for it
cannot properly assess Iraq's progress in complying with its
resolutions, notably in the nuclear field.
</P>
<P>
Russian Foreign Ministry called on all sides "to show restraint
and avoid steps which could lead to further deterioration of the
situation."
</P>
<P>
The ministry believed that the Special Commission "would
facilitate the closure of Iraq's disarmament files and the
introduction of a monitoring regime," and the Security Council
could pass a resolution on lifting the oil embargo against Iraq.
</P>
