<HEADLINE> 2 Lebanese Civilians Wounded in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Two Lebanese civilians were
wounded in south Lebanon Thursday during an Israeli artillery
bombardment, the state-run National News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli troops pounded the village of Kfar Tibnet on the
edge of the Israeli occupied south Lebanon, leading to the injury
of the two civilians, said the news agency.
</P>
<P>
The shelling also damaged several villagers' houses and set
surrounding crop fields and farms on fire.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli attack came as a retaliation for the previous
offensives launched by guerrillas of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah,
or Party of God.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, a Hezbollah guerrilla was killed and another
wounded by an Israeli shell.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Thursday morning, Hezbollah launched retaliation
attacks on a number of Israeli posts in the occupied zone.
</P>
<P>
The conflicts between Israeli forces and Lebanese guerrillas
have been going on since Israel set up a 1,200-square-kilometer
self-styled security zone in south Lebanon in 1985 to protect its
north from cross-border attacks by Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Heavy losses the Israeli forces suffered have raised question
in Israel about the wisdom of maintaining troops in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In April this year, Israel offered to withdraw its troops from
the region on the condition of Beirut's security guarantee for its
northern borders.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon rejected the offer and asked Israel to leave the
country unconditionally. 
</P>
</TEXT>
