<HEADLINE> China Urges to Settle Issue of Iraq Through Negotiation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Negotiations and Dialogues
are the only proper ways to solve the current issue regarding to
Iraq's Weapons inspection, China reiterated here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the Security Council of the
United Nations was briefed by Richard Butler, Executive Chairman
of the United Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of
dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, on his recent
visit to Iraq, Qin Huasun, Chinese Ambassador to the United
Nations, said China is gravely concerned about the development
of the events in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Qin said China hopes that the dialogue with Iraq
will be resumed so as to properly solve the current problems
through negotiations and dialogues.
</P>
<P>
Qin said China supports the positive and constructive proposals
made by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan who said that the Security
Council should make a comprehensive evaluation on the
progress made by Iraq in its destruction of prohibited weapons and
Security Council should establish direct dialogues with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Qin reiterated China's position that the Security Council
resolutions should be implemented comprehensively and in a
balanced way. Iraq should comply with Security Council
resolutions fully and the Security Council should look at the
progress made by Iraq in the dismantling of its weapons of mass
destruction in an objective manner in accordance with relevant
Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Qin stressed that the Security Council should make an objective
and timely evaluation of the progress Iraq has made so that the
files of weapons can be closed and sanctions can be lifted at an
early date. 
</P>
