<HEADLINE> Uganda Army to Launch Anti-Rebel Surveillance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- President Yoweri Museveni
Thursday said the Uganda People's Defense Forces (UPDF) will
launch a full-time surveillance and combat operation against
rebels active in the western part of the country.
</P>
<P>
He revealed the plan when addressing Kasese district local
council, but did not give more details of the plan, Radio Uganda
reported Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the operation is to trace the Allied Democratic
Forces (ADF) rebels in the war affected areas of Kasese, Kabarole
and Bundibugyo, all of which are frequently haunted by the ADF
rebels.
</P>
<P>
Following the June 8 massacre in which more than 80 students
were burnt to death and over 100 others abducted, the ADF rebels
attacked Kasese town on August 1, killing at least 16 people
including two UPDF soldiers and two police constables.
</P>
<P>
Museveni said the operation will also include modern night
vision military equipment, and aircraft which can sight the enemy
at night.
</P>
<P>
ADF rebels have been waging war against the government from
western Uganda since 1996. But on several occasions they have
infiltrated the capital, hurled grenades at unsuspecting sites,
claiming lives and sending people into panic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
