<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 14 Nations to Join NATO Exercise in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Troops from 14 NATO member
states and NATO's Partnership for Peace partner countries will
participate in a training exercise near Tirana, Albania, in
mid-August, NATO said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The joint exercise, codenamed as Cooperative Assembly'98, is
designed to develop a common understanding of peace support
operations and to practise interoperability between participating
nations.
</P>
<P>
Air, maritime and land forces will practise search, rescue,
close air support, medical evacuation and air drop procedures as
well as infantry peace support operation skills.
</P>
<P>
NATO officials said that the scheduled training exercise will
help refine and validate the procedures and requirements necessary
for military forces from NATO and Partnership for Peace countries
to operate effectively together.
</P>
<P>
The exercise will be under the command of NATO's Allied Forces
Southern Europe.
</P>
<P>
Participating in the exercise will be Belgium, Britain, Canada,
France, Germany, Greece, Italy, Lithuania, the Netherlands,
Russia, Spain, Turkey, the United States and hosts Albania.
</P>
<P>
Six other countries will also take part in the exercise as
observers
</P>
<P>
The Cooperative Assembly'98 exercise, slated for between August
17 and 22, will be held within the framework of the Partnership
for Peace program that was launched in January 1994.
</P>
<P>
The program aims at improving the understanding and cooperation
with the armed forces of central and eastern European countries
and with several central Asian and Caucasus countries as well and
thus foster enhanced security relationship between the western
military alliance and its partners.
</P>
<P>
The exercise in Albania was originally scheduled for next year
but was advanced to show NATO's concern about the crisis in the
neighboring Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
NATO also prepares a joint military exercise in Macedonia,
another Partnership for Peace member country, in September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
