<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- Moroccan Minister of Tourism Hassan Al Sabbar said his
country will play host to some 2 million tourists by the year-end,
besides about 800,000 Moroccan expatriates living abroad.
</P>
<P>
He said the number of tourists increased during the first six
months of this year by 14 percent, whereas the revenues grew by 17
percent and hotel occupancy rose 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
He said the government gives special attention to the tourism
sector, a source of hard currency earns and an incentive to
foreign and local investments.
</P>
<P>
The government is expected to reconsider the tourism investment
law and to incorporate further privileges which are absent in
former laws.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- The National Bureau of Tunisia's Ministry of Tourism
has concluded a set of studies on the trends and efficiency of
tourism.
</P>
<P>
According to a bureau source, the studies dwelt on German and
British tourist markets as well as those in east Europe. They
pointed out that there were 10 million Germans wishing to visit
Tunisia, while the number of British tourists can amount to 23
million.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- The quantity of olive oil exported from the biggest
Tunisian port of Soussa reached 31,000 tonnes since the beginning
of the current season.
</P>
<P>
Official estimates by the Tunisian national bureau for oil say
that additional quantities of approximately 950 tonnes will be
exported in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
This is compared with 21,700 tonnes exported from Soussa during
the same period of last year. 
</P>
