<HEADLINE> Pentagon Says NATO to Hold Exercises Near Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) will hold exercises in Albania beginning next
week and in Macedonia next month to warn against Yugoslavia on the
conflict in Kosovo, the Pentagon said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a regular briefing, Defense Department spokesman
Ken Bacon told reporters that NATO plans for possible military
intervention in the Kosovo situation could be completed by the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
He said the military exercises, to be held August 17-22 in
Albania and September 10-18 in Macedonia -- would involve forces
from a large number of NATO countries and eastern bloc nations
under the alliance's Partnership for Peace (PFP) program.
</P>
<P>
The Albania exercise was planned following NATO ministerial
meetings early this Summer while the Macedonia peacekeeping
exercise had been tentatively planned for some time, Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
NATO'S patience was wearing thin over the continuing violence
in Kosovo, he stressed, referring to the conflict in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"NATO will have to decide what triggers its intervention," he
said. "I think that every day the violence continues, it brings
the NATO community closer to consensus on this."
</P>
<P>
Bacon declined to give details of the plans, but said the
packages covered "a wide range of military options."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and its allies have blamed Yugoslavia for the crisis
in Kosovo, claiming that Belgrade should take all the major
responsibilities for it.  
</P>
