<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Uganda Thursday reiterated its
stance of good-neighborlihood with and non-interference in Congo
(K), where military conflicts have reportedly been going on for
days.
</P>
<P>
In a statement broadcast by Radio Uganda Thursday evening, the
government said it wishes to reiterate its policy of good
neighborliness with all her neighbors and non-interference in the
internal affairs of other countries.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time the Ugandan government has publicly
aired its attitude toward the recent fightings against the L.
Kabila administration in the eastern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
Uganda appreciates all efforts aimed at finding a peaceful
settlement to the internal conflict in the Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC). It supports the initiative of the Organization of
African Union to hold a regional summit in Harare on August 7 in
order to find a lasting settlement to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the Ugandan government is doing everything
possible to ensure the safety of its nationals living in DRC and
will continue to monitor the situation there.
</P>
<P>
Media reports here said the recent rebellion in Africa's third
largest country was against President Laurent Kabila, accusing
him of nepotism and failing to run the country properly.
</P>
<P>
