<HEADLINE> U.S. Opposes Easing of Sanction on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. State Department
said on Thursday that Washington would oppose any easing of
sanctions against Iraq until Baghdad complies with U.N.
resolutions on weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
"We will oppose any change in the sanctions regime until Iraq
complies," spokesman James Foley told reporters.
</P>
<P>
But Foley said the United States did not consider the latest
dispute to be a crisis.
</P>
<P>
The latest dispute came as talks between chief U.N. weapons
inspector Richard Butler and Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq
Aziz broke down earlier this week becauser of Butlter's refusal
to declare that all Iraq's weapons of mass destruction had been
accounted for.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Thursday the White House said Iraq's decision to
freeze weapons inspections was unacceptable and vowed to keep
pressure on Iraq unless it complies with the U.N. resolution.
</P>
<P>
"This noncompliance is completely unacceptable," White House
spokesman P.J. Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
"We will not allow Iraq access to the resources necessary to
restart their weapons of mass destruction program," he said. "We
will keep the pressure on until Iraq complies fully" with the
U.N.-mandated inspections program.
</P>
<P>
Crowley also said Iraq failed to provide required escorts on
Thursday to a U.N. inspections team seeking to leave its
compound in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He said the failure to provide the escorts was an indication
that Iraq's threats of noncompliance were being carried out
although there had been no inspection scheduled.
</P>
<P>
"We have evidence on the ground that Iraq is beginning to
follow through on its threats," Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
He said Bill Richardson, U.S. ambassador to the United
Nations, had broken off a vacation to attend a U.N. Security
Council briefing by chief weapons inspector Richard Butler on
Thursday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
