<HEADLINE> UN Urges Early Resumption of Dialogue Between </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Iraq's announcement to
freeze the cooperation with the United Nations Special Commission
(UNSCOM) and the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) was totally
unacceptable, the Security Council of the United Nations stressed
here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the Council was briefed by Richard Butler,
Executive Chairman of UNSCOM in charge of scraping Iraq's weapons
of mass destruction, on his recent visit to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the Council received the briefing, the
current President of the Council and Slovenia's Ambassador to the
United Nations Turk Danilo said Iraq's decision contravenes with
the relevant resolutions of the Security Council and the Memorandum of
Understanding signed by the U.N. Secretary-General and the
Authorities of Iraq in February this year.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council noted that the announcement was made
after a period of improved cooperation and some tangible
progress since the signing of the Memorandum.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council reiterated its endorsement in the
resolution 1154 of 1998 and the Memorandum of Understanding and
reaffirms its support for UNSCOM and IAEA in the implementation
of their mandate and calls for an early resumption of
dialogue between Iraq and UNSCOM and IAEA.
</P>
<P>
 The Security Council intended to respond favorably to the
future progress made in the disarmament process and affirmed its
commitment to comprehensive implementation of its resolutions in
particular resolution 687 of 1991.  
</P>
