<HEADLINE> Rwandan FM Denies Involvement in Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Rwandan Foreign Minister Gasana
Anastase Thursday denied his country's involvement in the
on-going conflicts between soldiers of rebel Banyamulenge and the
government in Congo (Kinshasa).
</P>
<P>
Rwanda's foreign policy now stresses on good neighborlihood,
said Anastase in Mazabuka, 100 kilometers south of Lusaka,
according to Zambia News Agency ZANA.
</P>
<P>
He noted that "Rwanda has no connection to the on-going
conflict in the Democratic Republic of Congo. The policy of our
government is good relations with other countries, especially our
neighbors."
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan foreign minister, who arrived in Zambia Wednesday
accompanying President Posteur Bizimingu for a three-day visit,
said his government has a great challenge to reconstruct the
country and has no time for involvement in conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda does not want to be disturbed to derail its mission of
rebuilding the country, he stressed, adding that Rwanda did help
Congo (K)'s President Laurent Kabila topple its predecessor
Mobutu Sese Seko in May last year.
</P>
<P>
When asked to explain as to whether the Banyamulenge in
eastern Congo are actually his country's nationals, Anastase said
Rwanda has no citizens in its western neighbor.
</P>
<P>
"We have no Rwandans living in eastern Congo. That is why we
decided to withdraw our forces which helped President Kabila
remove dictator Mobutu," said Anastase.
</P>
<P>
On future relations with the Congolese government, the foreign
minister said relations will remain good so long as rwanda is not
disturbed in its efforts to reconstruct the country ravaged by
years of civil war.
</P>
<P>
Early Wednesday, visiting Rwandan President Bizimingu also
denied his country's involvement in Congo's conflicts, saying
Rwanda has no reason to get involved in the conflict which
followed the repatriation of Rwandan soldiers last week.
</P>
<P>
However, the Congolese government Monday accused Rwanda, its
former ally, of invading the country and called on the U.N.
Security Council to order an immediate retreat of the troops that
invaded its territory. 
</P>
