<HEADLINE> U.S. Air Force Suspends B-2 Bombers Training </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Air Force has
suspended training missions for its B-2 stealth bombers after
problems with the aircraft's crew ejection system were found.
</P>
<P>
The suspension was called as "a potential problem associated
with initiators which operate the air crew ejection system" had
been discovered during routine acceptance testing, the Air Force
said in statement Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The B-2 stealth bomber was designed in the 1970s and 1980s to
be able to dodge Soviet radar in a potential conflict. The first
B-2 entered service in December 1993 and there are eight such
planes in the Air Force and all are based with the 509th Bomb Wing
at Whiteman Air Force Base in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, small holes were discovered on one of the
wings of one of the bombers.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the suspension was temporary and
precautionary. It would not interfere with the aircraft's ability
to be deployed in combat.
</P>
<P>
"Each aircraft has eight initiators and all will be replaced as
a safety precaution. Each aircraft will resume peacetime training
as soon as replacement parts are installed and inspections are
complete," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The 2-billion-dollar warplane can drop either nuclear or
conventional bombs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
