<HEADLINE> Ugandan FM Ends Visit to Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan First Deputy Premier and
Minister of Foreign Affairs Eriya Kategaya has concluded his
four-day official visit to Israel with both sides agreeing to
strengthen economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
During talks with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu,
Kategaya briefed him on the improving economic situation in
Uganda and the Great Lakes Region which is offering great
investment opportunities, Radio Uganda reported Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
They discussed matters of bilateral interest in areas of
cooperation such as investment promotion and agro-industry.
</P>
<P>
Both sides agreed to analyze priority areas for cooperation
followed by signing and implementation of the agreements.
</P>
<P>
The peace process in the Middle East and the situation in the
Great Lakes Region were also high on their agenda.
</P>
<P>
Kategaya said on the basis of forming a regional economic
integration body, the idea of forming a political federation,
proposed recently by President Yoweri Museveni, is being
considered by the three east African countries as well as Rwanda,
Burundi and the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
Accompanied by a large trade delegation, the Ugandan foreign
minister aimed to promote Uganda's economic ties with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel used to be deeply involved in Uganda's economic life in
the 1960s. It built roads and extensive agricultural projects in
northern Uganda.
</P>
<P>
But with the coming into power of Idi Amin in 1971, their
bilateral ties began to show signs of deterioration after Israel
refused to give Amin the fund he needed badly to revitalize the
shattered economy.
</P>
<P>
Kategaya's visit is seen as a clear signal that a new active
phase of contacts between the two former friends is at hand.
</P>
</TEXT>
