<HEADLINE> Jordan Urges Israel, Palestinians to Move on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's Crown Prince Hassan here
Thursday urged the Palestinians and Israel to enter into final
status talks, saying that the time is ripe.
</P>
<P>
He made the call after meeting separately with Palestinian
chief negotiator Saeb Erekat and Israeli Minister of Internal
Security Avigdor Kahalani.
</P>
<P>
Hassan said that it is time to close the chapter of second
Israeli troops redeployment in the West Bank, and move on to the
third redeployment and start the final status negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The regent said that his judgment is based on the belief that
the current Israeli-Palestinian negotiations have almost reached
the threshold of achievements.
</P>
<P>
He said that the efforts exerted by the Palestinians in these
negotiations are very "effective."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hassan said that the United States, as a full
partner of the peace process, should consolidate the achievements
of the two parties, especially at this crucial moment.
</P>
<P>
Erekat, who arrived in Amman early Thursday to deliver a
message to Hassan from Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, played a
different tune. He told reporters that Israel has so far failed to
comply with the signed peace agreements and rejects a U.S. peace
proposal.
</P>
<P>
He called on the U.S. to publicize the details of its proposal
as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Kahalani arrived here later on a one-day trip. He held three
hours of talks with Hassan and delivered a letter from Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Kahalani said a solution to the deadlock of the peace process
is imminent.
</P>
<P>
Direct Palestinian-Israeli talks were resumed last month but
the two sides are still apart on the U.S. initiative calling for a
13.1 percent Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have accepted the U.S. idea, but Israel still
resisted it, citing security concerns.
</P>
<P>
Israel suggested that it hands over 10 percent and limits
Palestinian rule over the other 3 percent which will be designed
as a "nature reserve."
</P>
<P>
Jordan has been sharply criticized Israel for its hardline
policies and kept a close eye on the developments of the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
It maintains regular contacts with Israeli government, its
opposition parties, the Palestinians as well as Egypt in order to
play a role in the process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
