<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Bankers Urged to End Strike  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan business circles
Thursday called for a quick end to the nationwide bank strike
</P>
<P>
Hardest hit are exporters, manufacturers, the tourism sector
and the foreign currency market, economic analysts said.
</P>
<P>
However, some 12,000 striking bank workers raised the stakes
Thursday, demanding the removal of Finance Minister Simeon
Nyachae as part of a deal to end the crisis caused by the
introduction of the new tax of their low-interest loans.
</P>
<P>
"The tax must be scrapped completely. The tax must go and then
Simeon Nyachae must follow," All Banks Shop Stewards leader Jacob
Opiyo told some 5,000 bank workers in downtown Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
During the day, the Nairobi Stock Exchange recorded a 91
percent drop in turnover since Monday, as manufacturers warned
the Treasury would lose out on duties and VAT payable on the
imported goods if the strike continues.
</P>
<P>
Chris Kirubi, the chairman of the Kenya Association of
Manufacturers (KAM), Thursday described the strike as "a disaster
for the economy."
</P>
<P>
He called for a quick end to the crisis, saying: "if we go on
like this for another two to three weeks, many industries will
grind to a halt."
</P>
<P>
He said KAM members had recorded a 30 percent reduction in
manufacturing and incurred costs at Kenya's Indian Ocean port of
Mombasa, and at the Jomo Kenyatta International Airport, Nairobi,
as they could not pay for the release of their imports.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturers were also suffering from a shortage of
operational cash as most of their money is tied in the banks,
while foreign remittances are also inaccessible as importers
cannot open letters of credit for imports or exports, he said.
</P>
<P>
He spoke out as the bank employers announced they were
recruiting new staff to replace those they sacked Wednesday for
going on strike.
</P>
<P>
But the sacked 12,000 workers were free to apply for their own
jobs, the bank employers said.
</P>
<P>
A strike over the same issue paralyzed banking services
earlier this year but was called off when the government
suspended implementation of the tax.
</P>
<P>
The tax was re-imposed in June and a tax on other fringe
benefits was also introduced with the government citing the
current economic difficulties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0339 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Increases Pressure on Belgrade in Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright has told Yugoslav leaders to halt military
offensive in Kosovo, which she said increased the threat of a
military intervention.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Foley said Thursday that in
the message to Yugoslav leader Slobodan Milosevic, Albright
expressed the strong view that "the ongoing Serb offensive and the
unacceptable actions" only increase the chances of there being
military action on the part of NATO.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a separate briefing, Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon
said the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) will hold
exercises in Albania beginning next week and in Macedonia next
month.
</P>
<P>
Bacon also told reporters that NATO plans for possible military
intervention in the Kosovo situation could be completed by the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
Analysts fear that the increasing pressure from the U.S. will
again encourage the Kosovar ethnic Albanian extremists to launch
new offensives for independence, which is opposed by the
international community including the United States.
</P>
<P>
Albright's message was conveyed to Milosevic Wednesday by
Ambassador Chris Hill, the U.S. envoy to Macedonia who has been
spearheading U.S. attempts to halt the fighting.
</P>
<P>
Albright expressed "her shock and dismay over the effects of
the Serb military offensive in Kosovo," said Foley.
</P>
<P>
NATO has drawn up contingency plans for possible military
action in and around the Yugoslav province. The alliance had held
exercises in June in Albania and Macedonia as a threat to the Serb
forces.
</P>
<P>
However, it said later that it is far from making a decision on
military intervention when the separatist rebels defeated the Serb
forces on the battlefield.
</P>
<P>
During Thursday's regular briefing, Bacon said NATO's patience
is wearing thin over the continuing violence in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"NATO will have to decide what triggers its intervention," he
said. "I think that every day the violence continues, it brings
the NATO community closer to consensus on this."
</P>
<P>
Bacon declined to give details of the plans, but said the
packages cover "a wide range of military options."
</P>
<P>
The military exercises, to be held on August 17-22 in Albania
and on September 10-18 in Macedonia, will serve as a new warning
to Belgrade against its offensive in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The exercises involve forces from a large number of NATO
countries and Eastern bloc nations under the alliance's
Partnership for Peace program, Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
The Albania exercise was planned following NATO ministerial
meetings early this summer while the Macedonia peacekeeping
exercise had been tentatively planned for some time.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and its allies have blamed Yugoslavia for the crisis
in Kosovo, saying that Belgrade should take all the major
responsibilities for it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
