<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Congress Approves Opening up Nazi Files </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Congress approved a
legislation on Thursday to unseal thousands of classified U.S.
files on Nazi war crimes and criminals.
</P>
<P>
The Nazi War Crimes Disclosure Act, which passed the Senate in
June, was approved in the House on Thursday by unanimous voice
vote and will be sent to President Bill Clinton for signature.
Clinton has indicated his support.
</P>
<P>
The act would make it much easier for historians, researchers
and the public to view the documents dating to the Cold War years
that followed World War II.
</P>
<P>
Several federal agencies, including the Central Intelligence
Agency (CIA), the State Department and the Department of Defense,
previously refused to declassify the documents, citing national
security.
</P>
<P>
The bill would create a new multi-agency group to administer,
inventory and release documents.
</P>
<P>
It also would require the government to disclose now-secret
information about individuals who participated in Nazi war crimes,
what their relationship was to U.S. intelligence agencies and what
they received in return. 
</P>
</TEXT>
