<HEADLINE> U.S. Praised for Surrendering Rwandan Genocide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 6 (Xinhua) - The Registrar of the
International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) Thursday
appreciated the decision by a United States court to surrender a
Rwandan genocide suspect to the Tribunal.
</P>
<P>
In a statement reaching here, Agwu Ukiwe Okali said the
Tribunal welcomed the decision by Judge John Rainey of the U.S.
District Court in Laredo, Texas on ordering the surrender of ICTR
indictee Elizaphan Ntakirutimana to the Tribunal based in Arusha,
northern Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
"The Tribunal hopes that this decision will accelerate the
process of bringing Mr. Ntakirutimana, accused of genocide and
crimes against humanity, to face trial before the Tribunal," the
Registrar said.
</P>
<P>
Okali also expressed thanks to the U.S. government for its
efforts to cooperate with and render judicial assistance to the
Rwanda Tribunal.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Okali said that the Tribunal's first judgement was
expected this month in the case of Jean-Paul Akayesu, the former
burgomaster of Taba Commune in Gitarama Prefecture.
</P>
<P>
The Tribunal also expected to deliver its sentence on Jean
Kambanda, former Prime Minister of Rwanda at the end of this
month.
</P>
<P>
Kambanda is the first Rwandan suspect who had pleaded guilty
to genocide and crimes against humanity before the Tribunal on
May 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
A total of 35 suspects have been indicted so far by the ICTR,
founded by the United Nations following the Rwanda massacre in
April 1994 soon after President Juvenal Habyarimana, a Hutu, died
when his plane was shot down over capital Kigali.
</P>
<P>
More than half a million people, mostly Tutsis and moderate
Hutus, were reportedly killed in the three-month slaughter.
</P>
</TEXT>
