<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls on Congress to Extend Brady Law on Gun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Thursday urged Congress to extend the Brady law on gun control in
an effort to keep weapons out of the hands of criminals.
</P>
<P>
The president issued the appeal in the White House Rose Garden
alongside police officers and Jim Brady, the former presidential
spokesman for whom the law is named. He was shot and wounded
during the 1981 assassination attempt on President Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
Under the Brady law, which took effect in 1984, a five-day
waiting period is required for handgun purchases. The ban expires
on November 30.
</P>
<P>
"Too many crimes are committed within hours of a handgun
purchase," Clinton said. "The waiting period gives tempers time to
cool. It gives potential criminals the time to consider the
consequences."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that years of experience now show that this law
works and "we have to make it more effective, not less effective."
</P>
<P>
Since 1994, the Brady law has blocked handgun purchases by more
than 240,000 people with criminal records or a history of mental
instability. Last year, it stopped 69,000 gun purchases.
</P>
<P>
"How many people are alive today because of that law? We will
never know," Clinton said. "But no one doubts the number is very
large indeed."
</P>
<P>
Clinton asked Congress not to water down the law with
amendments that he says would thwart the FBI's ability to perform
the instant background checks and maintain important records.
</P>
<P>
The issue was raised weeks after the shootings occurred inside
the Capitol, in which two Capitol police officers were killed and
a tourist was injured. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
