<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya, Uganda Sign Accord on Cargo Storage  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Kenya and Uganda Thursday signed
an agreement in which Kenya pledges to provide sufficient space
Uganda's goods.
</P>
<P>
It was also agreed that as from September this year, the Kenya
Port Authority (KPA) will open a special window at the port for
processing Uganda transit cargo documents in order to expedite
documentation flow.
</P>
<P>
The accord was signed by Kenyan Minister for East African and
Regional Cooperation Nicholas Biwott and Brig Moses Ali, Uganda's
Second Deputy Prime Minister and Minister for Tourism, Trade and
Industry, according to media reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Under the pact, KPA and Kenya Revenue Authority will work out
modalities for starting operations at western Kenya's Eldoret
Inland Container depot to speed up the handling of Ugandan goods.
</P>
<P>
The move was said to be a follow-up to the state visit by
Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi to Uganda in May.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also discussed issues on the tea bonding
requirement for Uganda tea exported through Kenya, which has now
been waived.
</P>
<P>
Although Kenya remains among the main exporters to Uganda, the
value of Kenyan imports to Uganda dropped by 43 million U.S.
Dollars last year due to Uganda's industrialization and the
availability of South African products.
</P>
<P>
Imports from Kenya fell from 280 million Dollars in 1995 to
200 million Dollars in 1996 and 157 million Dollars in 1997,
according to the official data. 
</P>
</TEXT>
