<HEADLINE> Chiluba Concerned About Congo (K) Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba has said the situation in Congo (K) is causing great
anxiety and sadness on the African continent, Zambia News Agency
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a dinner hosted for the visiting Rwandan President
Pasteur Bizimingu here Wednesday night, Chiluba also said it is
regrettable that the new government of Congo (K) cannot be given
a chance to rebuild the country because of the conflict between
the government and rebel Banyamulenge soldiers.
</P>
<P>
"We look forward to a quick resolution to the on-going
conflict to enable that country to resume its economic and
political reconstruction program," said the president.
</P>
<P>
He also stated that the resurgence of armed conflicts in
Africa are a threat to the tremendous gains made in the region's
economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
It was saddening that Africa has continued to spend its scare
resources on resolving conflicts instead of national building,
Chiluba noted.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the same occasion, Rwandan president Bizimingu
stressed that African leaders must work to ensure that conflicts
are resolved if the continent has to develop.
</P>
<P>
He added that Africa must not allow influence from outside to
cause strife and divisions and that the continent could only be
developed by the Africans themselves.
</P>
<P>
During an official talks with Chiluba earlier Wednesday,
Bizimingu denied his country's involvement in the conflicts in
its western neighbor, saying that for the time being there is "no
particular reason" for Rwanda to get involved in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
However, Bizimingu, who arrived in Zambia Wednesday morning
for a three-day state visit, indicated that Rwanda may get
involved if necessary, saying: "if there are serious reasons to
be involved, maybe we will be."
</P>
<P>
The Congolese government Tuesday accused Rwanda of invading
its territory and called on the U.N. Security Council to order an
immediated retreat of the Rwandan troops. Meanwhile, it warned
all its neighbor against getting involved in its internal
conflict.
</P>
<P>
The conflicts Happened Sunday evening after Rwandan soldiers,
who helped President Laurent Kabila of Congo (Kinshasa) seize
power last year were ordered to return to their homeland.
</P>
</TEXT>
