<HEADLINE> Comoran Officials Slap Secessionists for Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Two senior officials of the
Comoros Thursday criticized secessionists in the country for
resisting peace efforts by the Organization of African Unity
(OAU) and other international organizations to restore peace.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement issued at the OAU headquarters here, the
country's foreign and justice ministers said failure on the part
of the secessionists to accept the peace efforts has created
social and economic crisis in the Comoros.
</P>
<P>
The ministers said the OAU could not be successful in its
efforts to regain national unity in the Comoros as the
secessionists fail to make clear-cut demands.
</P>
<P>
They said OAU has carried on with its efforts to attain a
peaceful settlement to the crisis in the country despite the
difficult situation there.
</P>
<P>
It was recalled that on August 3, last year, secessionists
from one of four islands of the federal Comoros, the Anjouan
Island, announced their independence.
</P>
<P>
They set up so-called "the state of Anjouan" and announced to
join France, the former colonial ruler of the islands. The
separative activity was immediately opposed by the OAU.
</P>
<P>
The Comoran crisis remains unsolved after the secessionists
refuse to accept OAU peace efforts. 
</P>
