<HEADLINE> Nigeria Names New State Administrators, Electoral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian leader General Abdulsalam
Abubakar Thursday announced the appointment of new military
administrators for the country's 36 states, the state television
stations, TV NTA said.
</P>
<P>
The appointment was announced after a joint meeting of the
ruling Provisional Ruling Council and the National Council of
State in Abuja, the federal capital.
</P>
<P>
The National State Council, comprising all military
administrators, was dissolved before the new appointment.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's meeting also approved a new independent electoral
body, the National Electoral Commission (NECON), which was sacked
by Abubakar on July 20.
</P>
<P>
The new electoral body which has 14 members, was chaired by
Justice Ife Omokusi Okwata.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, however, failed to produce a new cabinet, as it
has been widely expected.
</P>
<P>
General Abubakar took the power on June 9 after the sudden
death of late military leader General Sani Abacha. He sacked the
cabinet of Abacha on July 8.
</P>
<P>
On July 20, Abubakar announced a new transition program by
which he promised to hand over to an elected civilian government
on May 29, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar sacked all the political parties as well as the
electoral body, saying that the transition program under Abacha
has lost its credibility due to massive rigging.
</P>
<P>
Lieutenant Colonel, A.U. Obi (Abia State), Lieutenant Colonel,
P.E. Obi (Bayelsa State), Colonel D.O. Oneya (Benue State), Wing
Commander, L.N. Haruna (Borno State), are on the list of the new
administrators. 
</P>
</TEXT>
