<HEADLINE> Kenya's Barclays Bank Pretax Profit Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Barclays Bank of Kenya, a
leading bank in this east African country, announced Thursday a
14 percent increase of its pre-tax profits in the first half of
this year.
</P>
<P>
Pre-tax profits for the six month to June 30 were posted at
2.118 billion Shillings (some 36 million Dollars), compared to
1.866 billion Shillings (some 32 million Dollars) for the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
The bank's Managing Director Gareth George, when expressing
satisfaction with the half-year's performance, noted that lending
growth had still been constrained by high interest rates and the
poor state of the economy.
</P>
<P>
Prospects for the full year looked promising but would be
influenced by the general performance of the country's economy,
George told media Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The bank also announced a one point reduction in its base
lending rate to 24 percent, effective from September 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
George expressed optimism that the downward trend in statutory
cash ratio and Treasury Bill rates would facilitate further
reductions in commercial bank lending rates.
</P>
<P>
Interest rates on benchmark 90 day Treasury bills are
currently around 24.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
George called for a quick resolution to the some 12,000 Kenyan
bank workers' strike launched Monday, saying the protest strike
against a new tax on bank staff loans is having a detrimental
effect on customer service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
