<HEADLINE> UK Supports U.N. Statement on Iraqi Arms Inspection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook said Thursday Britain backed the U.N. Security Council's
statement that Iraq's suspension of cooperation with U.N. arms
inspectors was "totally unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
The Security Council made the above announcement after the
talks between U.N. chief arms inspector Richard Butler and the
Iraqi leadership collapsed early this week and Iraq pledged to
halt all cooperation with the U.N. Special Commission for
Disarmament in Iraq (UNSCOM).
</P>
<P>
Cook said in a statement issued Thursday, "The U.N. Security
Council's message to Iraq is swift and clear: the international
community is united in rejecting Iraq's demand for a rewriting of
the rules under which UNSCOM operates."
</P>
<P>
"If (Iraqi President) Saddam Hussein is genuine in wanting
sanctions lifted, he cannot continue to defy the will of the
international community," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
Cook stressed that Iraq should "take heed" of the U.N.'s demand
that Iraq resume full and unconditional cooperation with the
UNSCOM and allow it full access to carry out its inspections.
</P>
<P>
"Only when UNSCOM has completed its work, can the U.N. Security
Council take action on sanctions," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
