<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980807.0353 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Needs to Be Engaged More Closely: Annan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said Thursday that the United Nations needs to engage
Iraq much more closely in resolving the question of arms
inspection in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who phoned Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz
Thursday morning, told the Security Council that he made it clear
to Aziz that Iraq's demands on the restructuring of U.N. Special
Commission for disarmament in Iraq, or UNSCOM, "are unacceptable
to the Security Council and the United Nations as a whole."
</P>
<P>
The council held informal consultations on Thursday to hear
UNSCOM Chairman Richard Butler's briefing on the breakdown of his
talks with the Iraqi authorities this week, which was followed by
a decision by Iraq to suspend cooperation with U.N. arms
inspectors unless conditions it sets are met.
</P>
<P>
It demands equal representation of the member states of the
Security Council on UNSCOM, a relocation of UNSCOM headquarters to
Geneva from New York and a rotation of UNSCOM chairmanship among
the five permanent members of the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"In any case it is not for a single member state to dictate the
organization how it should structure its activities," Annan said,
adding that the Iraqi position is clearly in violation of the
resolutions of the council and the accord he reached with Iraq in
February to defuse an inspection crisis.
</P>
<P>
However, he said: "having studied the Iraqi declarations
carefully and spoken to Mr. Aziz, it is my judgement that the
Iraqi Government's position on this matter is not a closed one."
</P>
<P>
"It appears that the Government of Iraq has developed the view
that its record of compliance is not satisfactorily recognized by
UNSCOM or by the Security Council," he said, continuing:
</P>
<P>
"It is my view that rather than allowing this situation to
deteriorate into a crisis, the Security Council should seek to
engage with the Iraqi authorities in order to resolve the problem.
</P>
<P>
"I would propose that the Security Council give some thought to
the larger questions involved in this matter by undertaking a
comprehensive review of the entire issue.
</P>
<P>
"This would include taking stock of Iraqi compliance with
relevant Security Council resolutions, the recognition of progress
made in a number of areas, and examining ways forward, bearing in
mind the ultimate objective of the exercise which is to ensure
that Iraq is effectively disarmed and that the Iraqi people are
enabled to take their place among the community of nations, free
of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
"The comprehensive review should involve a more direct dialogue
than has occurred hitherto between the the Government of Iraq and
the Security Council itself on the contentious issues before us."
</P>
<P>
Later, the Secretary-General told reporters that in taking the
comprehensive review, it might be helpful to engage the Iraqis
much more closely.
</P>
<P>
Ruling out the need to apply any military means to pressure
Iraq to comply with U.N. resolutions, Annan said the determination
of the Security Council to see the tasks through "will help us
alone". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
